const GUESSES = [
  {id:1,title:`Umbrellas Sold in Mumbai`,question:`Estimate the number of umbrellas sold in Mumbai in a year.`,difficulty:`Easy`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Segment Mumbai households by income, estimate umbrellas owned per household, divide by average product life.`,assumptions:[`Mumbai's population is approximately 2 crore (20 million).`,`Average household size is 4 persons → 50 lakh households.`,`Income split: Low 35%, Middle 50%, High 15%.`,`Average umbrellas owned per household: Low 1.5, Middle 2.5, High 4.`,`Average useful life of an umbrella: Low and Middle income 6 years; High income 4 years (replaced more frequently).`,`Only household umbrellas are considered; institutional purchases (schools, hotels) are excluded.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Number of households by income segment`,body:`Total households in Mumbai = 20M ÷ 4 = 50 lakh.
• Low income (35%): 17.5 lakh households
• Middle income (50%): 25 lakh households
• High income (15%): 7.5 lakh households`,result:`50 lakh households total`},{heading:`Step 2: Total umbrellas owned by each segment`,body:`Umbrellas owned = households × average umbrellas per household.
• Low: 17.5L × 1.5 = 26.25 lakh umbrellas
• Middle: 25L × 2.5 = 62.5 lakh umbrellas
• High: 7.5L × 4 = 30 lakh umbrellas`,result:`Low 26.25L · Middle 62.5L · High 30L`},{heading:`Step 3: Annual sales = umbrellas owned ÷ useful life`,body:`Annual replacement demand = total umbrellas ÷ useful life in years.
• Low: 26.25L ÷ 6 = 4.4 lakh/year
• Middle: 62.5L ÷ 6 = 10.4 lakh/year
• High: 30L ÷ 4 = 7.5 lakh/year

Total annual sales = 4.4 + 10.4 + 7.5 = 22.3 lakh`,result:`≈ 22 lakh umbrellas/year`}],answer:`Approximately 22 lakh umbrellas are sold in Mumbai each year.`,insight:`Sanity check: Mumbai has about 50 lakh households. If 1 in 2 households buys an umbrella every year, that gives 25 lakh — consistent with our estimate of 22 lakh.`},
  {id:2,title:`Delhi-Gurgaon Toll Plaza Daily Revenue`,question:`Estimate the daily revenue of the Delhi-Gurgaon Expressway toll plaza.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Revenue Estimation`,approach:`Estimate the number of vehicles passing per toll booth across three traffic bands, apply a weighted average fare, then multiply by the number of active booths.`,assumptions:[`The toll plaza operates 24 hours, 7 days a week.`,`Two-wheelers and three-wheelers are exempt from toll.`,`Two vehicle types pay toll: passenger cars (70% of chargeable traffic, Rs 30 each) and heavy vehicles/trucks (30%, Rs 70 each).`,`Each booth processes one vehicle every 15 seconds = 4 vehicles per minute = 240 per hour at full capacity.`,`Traffic varies by time of day: High traffic 8 hours/day (100% capacity), Medium traffic 8 hours/day (60% capacity), Low traffic 8 hours/day (30% capacity).`,`The plaza has 20 active toll booths operating simultaneously.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Vehicles per booth per day`,body:`Vehicles per booth = (8 hrs × 240/hr × 100%) + (8 hrs × 240/hr × 60%) + (8 hrs × 240/hr × 30%)
= 1,920 + 1,152 + 576 = 3,648 ≈ 3,600 vehicles per booth per day.`,result:`3,600 vehicles/booth/day`},{heading:`Step 2: Weighted average fare per vehicle`,body:`Weighted fare = (70% × Rs 30) + (30% × Rs 70)
= Rs 21 + Rs 21 = Rs 42 per vehicle.`,result:`Rs 42 weighted average fare`},{heading:`Step 3: Revenue per booth per day`,body:`Revenue per booth = 3,600 vehicles × Rs 42 = Rs 1,51,200 ≈ Rs 1.5 lakh per booth.`,result:`Rs 1.5 lakh/booth/day`},{heading:`Step 4: Total daily revenue across all booths`,body:`Total revenue = 20 booths × Rs 1.5 lakh = Rs 30 lakh per day.`,result:`Rs 30 lakh/day`}],answer:`The Delhi-Gurgaon toll plaza earns approximately Rs 30 lakh per day.`,insight:`Sanity check: The Delhi-Gurgaon Expressway is one of India's busiest corridors. An annual collection of ~Rs 110 crore from this estimate is in line with publicly reported NHAI toll revenues from major national highway plazas.`},
  {id:3,title:`National Newspaper Daily Revenue`,question:`Estimate the daily revenue of a leading national English daily newspaper in India.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Revenue Estimation`,approach:`Revenue = Circulation revenue + Print advertising revenue + Digital advertising revenue.`,assumptions:[`The newspaper has a national print circulation of approximately 30 lakh copies per day.`,`Cover price is Rs 6; after distributor margins the publisher retains Rs 3 per copy.`,`A standard broadsheet has 25 pages, each 60 cm × 40 cm = 2,400 sq. cm. Advertising occupies 25% of total space.`,`Print ad rate: Rs 5,000 per sq. cm for premium pages (front/back) and Rs 2,000 for interior pages; blended rate ≈ Rs 3,000/sq. cm.`,`Digital: the website has 25 million monthly users → ~8 million daily users. Average 5 ads per session, CTR 1%, CPC Rs 10.`,`Digital display impressions are priced on CPM basis: 8M users × 5 ads = 40M impressions at Rs 100 CPM = Rs 40 lakh.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Circulation revenue`,body:`30 lakh copies × Rs 3 net revenue per copy = Rs 90 lakh.`,result:`Rs 90 lakh/day`},{heading:`Step 2: Print advertising revenue`,body:`Ad area = 25 pages × 2,400 sq. cm × 25% = 15,000 sq. cm of ad space.
Revenue = 15,000 sq. cm × Rs 3,000 = Rs 4.5 crore.`,result:`Rs 4.5 crore/day`},{heading:`Step 3: Digital advertising revenue`,body:`8M daily users × 5 impressions × Rs 100 CPM ÷ 1,000 = Rs 40 lakh.
(Alternatively: 8M users × 5 ads × 1% CTR × Rs 10 CPC = Rs 40 lakh — consistent.)`,result:`Rs 40 lakh/day`},{heading:`Step 4: Total daily revenue`,body:`Total = Rs 90L (circulation) + Rs 450L (print ads) + Rs 40L (digital)
= Rs 580 lakh ≈ Rs 5.8 crore per day.`,result:`Rs 5.8 crore/day`}],answer:`A leading national English daily newspaper earns approximately Rs 5–6 crore per day, with print advertising contributing the bulk (~75%) of revenue.`,insight:`Note: Print advertising is the dominant revenue driver for Indian newspapers, contributing about 4× more than circulation. Digital revenue is growing but still a minor share.`},
  {id:4,title:`Smartwatch Market Size in India`,question:`Estimate the market size (annual revenue) of smartwatches in India.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Market Sizing`,approach:`Identify the addressable population, apply penetration rates by income segment, and multiply installed base by replacement cycle to get annual unit sales; multiply by average price.`,assumptions:[`India's population: 140 crore. Urban: 35% = 49 crore. Rural: 65% = 91 crore.`,`Smartwatch penetration is effectively limited to urban middle income and high income segments.`,`Urban income split: High 10%, Middle 40%, Low 30%, BPL 20%.`,`Target population = Urban High (4.9 crore) + Urban Middle (19.6 crore) = 24.5 crore.`,`Age filter: only 25–55 age group likely buys smartwatches = 40% of target = ~10 crore.`,`Penetration: High income 20%, Middle income 5%.`,`Average smartwatch price: Rs 8,000 (blending budget (Rs 3K–5K) and premium (Rs 15K–30K) segments).`,`Average replacement cycle: 4 years.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Urban high income smartwatch owners`,body:`Urban high income (age 25-55) = 4.9 cr × 40% = 1.96 crore.
Penetration 20% → owners = 0.39 crore ≈ 39 lakh.`,result:`39 lakh high income owners`},{heading:`Step 2: Urban middle income smartwatch owners`,body:`Urban middle income (age 25-55) = 19.6 cr × 40% = 7.84 crore.
Penetration 5% → owners = 0.39 crore ≈ 39 lakh.`,result:`39 lakh middle income owners`},{heading:`Step 3: Total installed base and annual sales`,body:`Total installed base = 39L + 39L = 78 lakh smartwatches.
Annual replacement sales = 78L ÷ 4 years = 19.5 lakh units/year.
New adopters = ~10% growth = ~8 lakh additional units.
Total annual unit sales ≈ 27–28 lakh units.`,result:`~28 lakh units/year`},{heading:`Step 4: Market size in rupees`,body:`Market size = 28 lakh units × Rs 8,000 average price
= Rs 22,400 crore ≈ Rs 22,000 crore.`,result:`Rs ~22,000 crore/year`}],answer:`The Indian smartwatch market is approximately Rs 20,000–25,000 crore annually.`,insight:`Industry reports (IDC, Counterpoint) put India's smartwatch shipments at ~40–50 million units annually in 2024, reflecting both the market's growth and strong budget tier. Our estimate of ~28 lakh is conservative — the market has grown faster than classical penetration models suggest, driven by sub-Rs 3,000 fitness bands.`},
  {id:5,title:`Number of Smokers in India`,question:`Estimate the number of smokers in India.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Segment the population by urban/rural and income level, apply gender-differentiated smoking probabilities by age group, and sum up.`,assumptions:[`India's population: 140 crore. Urban 40% = 56 crore; Rural 60% = 84 crore.`,`Smoking probability differs by gender: male smokers far outnumber female smokers in India.`,`Smoking prevalence varies by income: low income groups have higher rates of bidi/non-filtered cigarette use; high income groups have higher filtered cigarette use.`,`Age groups: 0–18 (no smoking), 18–30 (peak initiation), 30–50 (established habit), 50+ (declining due to health concerns).`,`Key assumption: Urban male smoking rate ~25%, urban female ~5%; Rural male ~35%, rural female ~3%.`,`Applicable age group (18–65) = approximately 55% of total population.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Urban smokers`,body:`Urban population aged 18–65 = 56 cr × 55% = 30.8 crore.
Gender split 50:50 → Male 15.4 cr, Female 15.4 cr.
Smoking rate: Male 25%, Female 5%.
Urban smokers = (15.4 cr × 25%) + (15.4 cr × 5%) = 3.85 cr + 0.77 cr = 4.62 crore.`,result:`4.62 crore urban smokers`},{heading:`Step 2: Rural smokers`,body:`Rural population aged 18–65 = 84 cr × 55% = 46.2 crore.
Gender split 50:50 → Male 23.1 cr, Female 23.1 cr.
Smoking rate: Male 35%, Female 3%.
Rural smokers = (23.1 cr × 35%) + (23.1 cr × 3%) = 8.1 cr + 0.69 cr = 8.79 crore.`,result:`8.79 crore rural smokers`},{heading:`Step 3: Total smokers`,body:`Total = 4.62 crore (urban) + 8.79 crore (rural) = 13.4 crore.
Rounding for estimation error: approximately 13–15 crore smokers in India.`,result:`~14 crore smokers`}],answer:`Approximately 13–15 crore (130–150 million) Indians smoke.`,insight:`WHO and GATS (Global Adult Tobacco Survey) data indicates India has approximately 270 million tobacco users in total (including smokeless tobacco like gutka/zarda), of which about 100–120 million are smokers. Our estimate of 130–150 million is in the right ballpark, with the slight overcount likely because we have not filtered out the youngest adult cohort (18–25) which has lower prevalence than the full adult average.`},
  {id:6,title:`Cheese Burst Pizzas Sold Daily in India`,question:`Estimate the number of cheese burst pizzas sold per day across India.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Estimate for a single city (Delhi), calculate from outlet count × orders per outlet × cheese burst share, then extrapolate nationally.`,assumptions:[`Focus on organised pizza chains (QSR format) only.`,`One outlet can serve from a 4 km radius → area served per outlet = π × 4² ≈ 50 sq km.`,`Delhi area = 1,484 sq km → number of outlets in Delhi ≈ 1,484 ÷ 50 ≈ 30 outlets.`,`Operating hours: 11 am to 11 pm = 12 hours. Peak hours (2-4 pm, 7-10 pm) = 5 hours; Non-peak = 7 hours.`,`Each outlet processes 3 orders in parallel, each taking 20 minutes.`,`Peak occupancy rate: 80%; Non-peak: 50%. Online/home delivery adds 50% to dine-in orders.`,`1 order = 1.5 pizzas on average. Cheese burst = 40% of all pizza orders.`,`Delhi = 10% of total metro/urban demand. Metros = 20% of India, Urban/suburban = 30% at 50% of metro rate, Rural = no outlets.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Orders per outlet (Delhi) per day`,body:`Peak hours: 3 parallel × (5 hrs × 60 min ÷ 20 min) × 80% occupancy = 3 × 15 × 0.8 = 36 orders.
Non-peak hours: 3 × (7 × 60 ÷ 20) × 50% = 3 × 21 × 0.5 = 31.5 ≈ 32 orders.
Dine-in orders per outlet = 36 + 32 = 68.
Including online/delivery (50% add-on): 68 × 1.5 = 102 orders per outlet per day.`,result:`~102 orders/outlet/day`},{heading:`Step 2: Cheese burst pizzas per outlet per day`,body:`Total pizzas = 102 orders × 1.5 pizzas/order = 153 pizzas.
Cheese burst share = 40% → 153 × 0.4 ≈ 61 cheese burst pizzas per outlet per day.`,result:`61 per outlet/day`},{heading:`Step 3: Scale to Delhi and all-India`,body:`Delhi: 30 outlets × 61 = 1,830 cheese burst pizzas/day in Delhi.
Delhi = 10% of metro demand → Metro demand = 18,300.
Urban/suburban = 30% of India's population at 50% metro rate → 18,300 × 1.5 = 27,450 additional.
Total India daily ≈ 18,300 + 27,450 ≈ 46,000 ≈ 45,000–50,000 cheese burst pizzas.`,result:`~45,000–50,000/day`}],answer:`Approximately 45,000–50,000 cheese burst pizzas are sold per day across India through organised pizza chains.`,insight:`Sanity check: If a major pizza chain has ~1,500 outlets nationally and each sells ~30 cheese burst pizzas per day, that gives 45,000 — consistent with our estimate.`},
  {id:7,title:`Table Tennis Balls Used in Delhi Per Day`,question:`Estimate the number of table tennis (TT) balls used in Delhi in a day.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Calculate the number of TT tables in commercial venues in Delhi, estimate matches per table per day, and apply average ball consumption per match.`,assumptions:[`Only commercially operated TT tables (sports clubs, recreational centres, coaching academies) are counted; private home tables add ~20%.`,`Number of TT tables in commercial spaces: Estimated from population and typical density.`,`Delhi population 2 crore; approximately 1 commercial TT table per 1,350 people = ~15,000 tables (rough benchmark from urban sports penetration data).`,`Each table operates an average of 14 hours per day.`,`One match takes ~14 minutes; 1 minute idle time between matches = 15 min per match slot.`,`Matches per table per day = 14 hrs × 60 min ÷ 15 min = 56 matches per table.`,`Average ball life = 5 matches before replacement.`,`Private home tables = 20% of commercial count.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Number of commercial TT tables in Delhi`,body:`Delhi has approximately 600 sports clubs, gyms, and recreational centres that offer TT facilities.
Assuming 10 tables on average per facility with TT = 6,000 commercial tables.
Adding coaching academies and standalone TT centres: ~2,000 more = 8,000 total commercial tables.`,result:`8,000 commercial tables`},{heading:`Step 2: Matches played per day across all tables`,body:`56 matches per table × 8,000 tables = 448,000 matches/day in commercial spaces.
Private home tables (20% additional): 1,600 tables × 56 × 50% usage = 44,800 matches.
Total matches per day ≈ 4.5 lakh matches.`,result:`~4.5 lakh matches/day`},{heading:`Step 3: Balls used per day`,body:`Balls used = Total matches ÷ Ball life = 4,50,000 ÷ 5 = 90,000 balls per day.`,result:`~90,000 TT balls/day`}],answer:`Approximately 90,000 table tennis balls are used in Delhi per day.`,insight:`Cross-check: If Delhi has 10,000 active TT players each using 9 balls per day (across all their matches), that gives 90,000 — consistent. The key driver is the large number of recreational matches played at clubs and gyms.`},
  {id:8,title:`People Wearing White Shirts in Delhi on a Weekday`,question:`Estimate the number of people wearing a white shirt in Delhi on any given weekday.`,difficulty:`Easy`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Segment Delhi's working and student population by occupation type, estimate the proportion likely to wear a white shirt, and aggregate.`,assumptions:[`Weekday assumption: offices, schools, colleges, and government institutions are operational.`,`Population of Delhi: 2 crore (20 million).`,`Age-wise split: 0-10 years (excluded) 15%, 10-25 years 25%, 25-60 years 45%, 60+ years 15%.`,`White shirts are commonly worn by formal office workers, college students in professional courses, and some government employees.`,`One person wears one shirt on a given day.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Working-age population (25–60 years)`,body:`25–60 years: 20M × 45% = 9 million.
Formal employment rate: 20% → 1.8 million formal workers.
Of formal workers: professional/office (60%) → 1.08M wear formal shirts.
White shirt share among formal workers: ~35% → 1.08M × 35% = 3.78 lakh ≈ 4 lakh.`,result:`~4 lakh from formal workers`},{heading:`Step 2: Student population (10–25 years)`,body:`10–25 years: 20M × 25% = 5 million students.
In colleges and professional courses: ~25% = 1.25M.
Of these, uniform/professional-dress courses requiring white shirts (engineering, medicine, hotel management): ~20% → 2.5 lakh.
White shirt use rate: ~50% on any day → 1.25 lakh.`,result:`~1.25 lakh from students`},{heading:`Step 3: Other segments`,body:`Government employees in uniform (white shirt required): ~2 lakh in Delhi government, police, banks → 50% wearing white on any day = 1 lakh.
Older adults (60+): 20M × 15% = 3M; ~5% wear white shirts = 1.5 lakh.`,result:`~2.5 lakh from other segments`},{heading:`Step 4: Total`,body:`Total = 4L + 1.25L + 1L + 1.5L = 7.75 lakh ≈ 8 lakh.`,result:`~8 lakh people`}],answer:`Approximately 8 lakh people wear a white shirt in Delhi on a typical weekday.`,insight:`Sanity check: That is 4% of Delhi's 2 crore population, which is reasonable given that white shirts are formal attire worn by a minority of people on any given day.`},
  {id:9,title:`Number of Schools in Delhi`,question:`Estimate the total number of schools in Delhi.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Estimate the school-going population in Delhi, estimate average school capacity by tier, and divide.`,assumptions:[`Population of Delhi: 2 crore. India is a young country; ~50% of the population is under 25.`,`School-going age: 4–17 years = 14 years out of 25-year span → ~28% of total population.`,`School attendance varies by income: Middle class and above (40%) → 100% attend; Lower class (40%) → 80% attend; BPL (20%) → 50% attend.`,`Schools are categorised as Small (40%), Medium (40%), and Large (20%).`,`Average students per school: Small = 600, Medium = 1,500, Large = 3,000; weighted average = 0.4×600 + 0.4×1500 + 0.2×3000 = 240+600+600 = 1,440.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: School-going population in Delhi`,body:`Total population aged 4–17 = 20M × 28% = 5.6 million.
Attendance rate (weighted): 0.4×100% + 0.4×80% + 0.2×50% = 40+32+10 = 82%.
Students actually in school = 5.6M × 82% = 4.6 million.`,result:`4.6 million students`},{heading:`Step 2: Average school capacity`,body:`Weighted average students per school:
0.4 × 600 + 0.4 × 1,500 + 0.2 × 3,000
= 240 + 600 + 600 = 1,440 students per school.`,result:`1,440 students/school (avg)`},{heading:`Step 3: Number of schools`,body:`Number of schools = 4.6M ÷ 1,440 = 3,194 ≈ 3,200.`,result:`~3,200 schools`}],answer:`Delhi has approximately 3,000–3,500 schools.`,insight:`The Delhi government's official data lists about 5,500 schools (including ~1,000 government, ~2,500 private, and ~2,000 aided/unaided). Our estimate of ~3,200 is in the right range; the gap arises because many small neighbourhood schools have fewer than 600 students and we may have underestimated the number of very small institutions.`},
  {id:10,title:`Daily Departing Flights from Delhi Airport`,question:`Estimate the number of flights departing from Indira Gandhi International Airport, Delhi, in a day.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Use the supply-side approach: estimate the number of active terminal gates and the turnaround time for each flight type to calculate maximum departures.`,assumptions:[`IGI Airport has 3 terminals: T1 (domestic, ~30 gates), T2 (underutilised), T3 (mixed, ~80 gates domestic + 40 international).`,`Total effective domestic gates: ~80; effective international gates: ~40.`,`Domestic flight turnaround time (gate occupancy): ~1.5 hours; International: ~3 hours.`,`Each gate can handle: Domestic = 24 ÷ 1.5 = 16 max departures/day; International = 24 ÷ 3 = 8.`,`Average utilisation: Domestic 65%; International 55% (accounting for night curfews and off-peak troughs).`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Maximum domestic departures`,body:`80 domestic gates × 16 max flights/day × 65% utilisation = 832.`,result:`~830 domestic departures`},{heading:`Step 2: Maximum international departures`,body:`40 international gates × 8 max flights/day × 55% utilisation = 176.`,result:`~175 international departures`},{heading:`Step 3: Total daily departures`,body:`Total departures = 830 + 175 = 1,005 ≈ 1,000 flights per day.
(Note: Total operations = departures + arrivals ≈ 2,000 movements/day.)`,result:`~1,000 departing flights/day`}],answer:`Approximately 1,000 flights depart from Delhi airport per day.`,insight:`Sanity check: Delhi airport is consistently ranked as India's busiest. DGCA data shows Delhi handles 1,300–1,500 total daily movements (arrivals + departures) in peak periods. Our estimate of ~1,000 departures implies ~2,000 movements, which is a slight overcount suggesting utilisation could be closer to 50% — a reasonable range for a major hub.`},
  {id:11,title:`Tractors Sold in India Per Year`,question:`Estimate the number of tractors sold in India per year.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Filter rural farming households down to those who are financially capable of purchasing a tractor, and divide by average tractor life.`,assumptions:[`India's population: 140 crore. Rural: 70% = 98 crore. Average household size: 5 → 19.6 crore rural households.`,`Primary agriculture sector: 80% of rural households depend on agriculture.`,`Farm-owning households (vs landless labourers): 20% of agricultural households.`,`Of farm owners, financially capable and with tractable land: 20% (rest are subsistence farmers with small/hilly plots).`,`Market access (near roads and dealers): 80% of capable farm owners.`,`Average useful life of a tractor: 10 years.`,`Urban demand (non-farming uses, construction) = ~10% of rural figure.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Eligible tractor-owning farm households`,body:`Rural households: 19.6 crore.
Agricultural: 80% = 15.7 crore.
Farm owners (vs labourers): 20% = 3.14 crore.
Financially capable with tractable land: 20% = 0.63 crore.
With market access: 80% = 0.50 crore = 50 lakh households.`,result:`50 lakh target households`},{heading:`Step 2: Annual tractor sales (replacement demand)`,body:`Annual sales = installed base ÷ average life = 50 lakh ÷ 10 years = 5 lakh tractors/year.`,result:`~5 lakh units/year (rural replacement)`},{heading:`Step 3: Adding urban/commercial demand`,body:`Urban and non-farm demand = 10% of rural = 0.5 lakh.
Total annual tractor sales = 5L + 0.5L ≈ 5.5 lakh.`,result:`~5.5 lakh tractors/year`}],answer:`Approximately 5–6 lakh tractors are sold in India annually.`,insight:`India is actually the world's largest tractor market by volume. Industry data (ICEMA, Tractors and Farm Equipment Limited) shows annual sales of 7–9 lakh units. Our estimate of 5.5 lakh is conservative because we under-count the new-adoption demand from farmers upgrading from bullocks to tractors for the first time, which adds meaningfully to replacement demand.`},
  {id:12,title:`Market Size of Electric Vehicles in India`,question:`Estimate the market size (annual revenue) of electric vehicles in India.`,difficulty:`Hard`,category:`Market Sizing`,approach:`Segment the 4-wheeler passenger vehicle market in Tier 1 cities. Identify EV-ready income groups, apply EV adoption penetration, and multiply by average EV price.`,assumptions:[`Scope: 4-wheeler passenger EVs only (excludes 2-wheelers, buses, commercial vehicles).`,`Focus on top 5 Tier-1 cities (Delhi, Mumbai, Bengaluru, Chennai, the city) with total population ~90 million.`,`Average household size: 4.5 → ~20 million households in these cities.`,`Income segments: Uber Rich 2% (0.4M HH), Upper Middle 38% (7.6M HH), Poor 60% (12M HH — no car ownership).`,`Car ownership rate: Uber Rich 100%, Upper Middle 50%.`,`Of car buyers, EV adoption: Uber Rich (100% premium car buyers) → EV innovators 10%; Upper Middle (80% normal, 20% premium) → EV innovators 5%.`,`Premium EV average price: Rs 22 lakh. Non-premium EV average price: Rs 6 lakh.`,`Car lifecycle: Uber Rich 5 years, Upper Middle 7 years.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Uber Rich EV buyers`,body:`0.4M HH × 100% car ownership = 0.4M cars.
Annual replacement: 0.4M ÷ 5 years = 80,000 cars/year.
10% choose EV → 8,000 premium EVs/year.`,result:`8,000 premium EVs/year`},{heading:`Step 2: Upper Middle EV buyers`,body:`7.6M HH × 50% car ownership = 3.8M cars.
Annual replacement: 3.8M ÷ 7 = 543,000 cars/year.
Of these, 20% buy premium (EV adoption 5%): 543K × 20% × 5% = 5,430 premium EVs.
80% buy standard (EV adoption 5%): 543K × 80% × 5% = 21,720 non-premium EVs.`,result:`~27,000 upper-middle EVs/year`},{heading:`Step 3: Market size calculation`,body:`Premium EV revenue: (8,000 + 5,430) × Rs 22 lakh = 13,430 × Rs 22L ≈ Rs 2,955 crore.
Non-premium EV revenue: 21,720 × Rs 6 lakh = Rs 1,303 crore.
Total market size ≈ Rs 2,955 + Rs 1,303 = Rs 4,258 crore ≈ Rs 4,000 crore.`,result:`Rs ~4,000 crore/year`}],answer:`The 4-wheeler EV market in India's top 5 cities is approximately Rs 4,000–5,000 crore annually.`,insight:`Note: EV adoption in India is accelerating rapidly. This estimate uses conservative penetration figures for 2023-24. The overall 4-wheeler EV market (all India, not just Tier-1) including newer models from Tata, MG, and Hyundai has grown to approximately Rs 15,000–20,000 crore. Our estimate captures roughly the top-city share.`},
  {id:13,title:`Daily Orders on a Leading E-Commerce Platform`,question:`Estimate the number of daily orders placed on a leading Indian e-commerce platform.`,difficulty:`Hard`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Filter India's internet users by geography and income, apply age-appropriate ordering frequency, and multiply by the platform's estimated market share.`,assumptions:[`India's mobile internet users: 800 million. Internet users among these: ~70% = 560 million.`,`Urban internet users: 60% = 336 million; Rural: 40% = 224 million.`,`Users segmented by income — Low, Middle, High — with different ordering frequencies.`,`Ordering frequency (orders/year): Rural Low 2, Rural Middle 4, Rural High 6; Urban Low 2, Urban Middle 5, Urban High 12.`,`Age filter: active online shoppers are aged 10–55 = ~65% of internet users.`,`Platform market share: 35% (consistent with major players like leading e-commerce platforms or Flipkart).`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Urban shoppers by income`,body:`Urban internet users: 336M × 65% active age = 218M.
Income split: Low 40% = 87M, Middle 40% = 87M, High 20% = 44M.
Annual orders: Low 87M×2 = 174M; Middle 87M×5 = 435M; High 44M×12 = 528M.
Total Urban annual orders = 1,137M.`,result:`1,137M urban orders/year`},{heading:`Step 2: Rural shoppers by income`,body:`Rural internet users: 224M × 65% = 146M.
Income split: Low 60% = 88M, Middle 30% = 44M, High 10% = 14.6M.
Annual orders: Low 88M×2 = 176M; Middle 44M×4 = 176M; High 14.6M×6 = 88M.
Total Rural annual orders = 440M.`,result:`440M rural orders/year`},{heading:`Step 3: Platform daily orders`,body:`Total e-commerce orders/year = 1,137M + 440M = 1,577M ≈ 1.6 billion.
Platform's 35% share = 560M orders/year.
Daily orders = 560M ÷ 365 = 1.53M ≈ 15 lakh orders/day.`,result:`~15 lakh orders/day`}],answer:`A major Indian e-commerce platform processes approximately 15–20 lakh orders per day.`,insight:`India's top e-commerce platforms publicly report or hint at 10–15 lakh daily orders during normal periods, spiking 3–5× during sale events like Diwali. Our estimate of 15 lakh is consistent with normal-day volumes for a platform with ~35% market share.`},
  {id:14,title:`Daily Revenue of a Major International Airport`,question:`Estimate the daily revenue of a major Indian international airport (comparable to Delhi or Mumbai).`,difficulty:`Hard`,category:`Revenue Estimation`,approach:`Sum four revenue streams: airline charges (landing + parking), retail and F&B rents, parking fees from passengers and visitors, and advertising.`,assumptions:[`Airport operates 24 hours. Approximately 500 flight movements per day (250 arrivals + 250 departures, mix of domestic and international).`,`Domestic flights: ~300 movements. International: ~200 movements.`,`Airline charges: Domestic fixed landing + parking fee = Rs 50,000 per movement; International = Rs 1,00,000 per movement.`,`Retail and F&B: Airport has 250 shops of varying sizes paying average rent of Rs 4,000/day each.`,`Passenger vehicles parking at Rs 100 per entry; ~25% of 1 lakh daily passengers use personal vehicle drop-off.`,`Advertising: 500 sq m of billboard/screen space at Rs 200 per sq m per day; plus 6 experience zones at Rs 75,000/day each.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Airline charges`,body:`Domestic: 300 movements × Rs 50,000 = Rs 1.5 crore.
International: 200 movements × Rs 1,00,000 = Rs 2.0 crore.
Total airline charges = Rs 3.5 crore.`,result:`Rs 3.5 crore`},{heading:`Step 2: Retail and F&B rent`,body:`250 shops × Rs 4,000/day = Rs 10 lakh.`,result:`Rs 10 lakh`},{heading:`Step 3: Parking revenue`,body:`Daily passengers: ~1 lakh (arrivals + departures).
25% use personal vehicle pickup/drop = 25,000 vehicles × Rs 100 = Rs 25 lakh.`,result:`Rs 25 lakh`},{heading:`Step 4: Advertising revenue`,body:`Billboards: 500 sq m × Rs 200 = Rs 1 lakh.
Experience zones: 6 × Rs 75,000 = Rs 4.5 lakh.
Total advertising = Rs 5.5 lakh.`,result:`Rs 5.5 lakh`},{heading:`Step 5: Total daily revenue`,body:`Total = Rs 350L + Rs 10L + Rs 25L + Rs 5.5L ≈ Rs 390L ≈ Rs 3.9 crore.
Rounding: approximately Rs 4 crore per day.`,result:`Rs ~4 crore/day`}],answer:`A major Indian international airport earns approximately Rs 4–5 crore per day.`,insight:`Delhi's IGIA (operated by DIAL) reported annual revenues of approximately Rs 3,800 crore in FY23, which works out to about Rs 10 crore per day — higher than our estimate. The gap reflects that our model understates the passenger service fee (PSF) and aeronautical charges, which are significant revenue components.`},
  {id:15,title:`Automobile Tyre Market Size in India`,question:`Estimate the size of the automobile tyre market in India (number of tyres sold annually).`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Market Sizing`,approach:`Estimate the total installed base of 4-wheeler passenger vehicles in India, then calculate annual tyre replacement demand separately for new and old cars.`,assumptions:[`Only 4-wheeler passenger cars are considered (excludes 2-wheelers, trucks, buses).`,`India's population: 140 crore; average household size 5 (rural), 4 (urban).`,`Urban households (30%): 140cr × 30% ÷ 4 = 10.5 crore households. Rural (70%): 140cr × 70% ÷ 5 = 19.6 crore.`,`Car ownership penetration by income: Urban High (30%) 95%, Urban Middle (50%) 60%, Urban Low (20%) 0%. Rural High (15%) 80%, Rural Middle (35%) 10%, Rural Low (50%) 0%.`,`Each car has 5 tyres (4 operational + 1 spare). Tyre life: 5 years. Car life: 12 years.`,`New cars (1/12 of total fleet each year) get 5 new tyres; older cars replace tyres every 5 years (5 tyres ÷ 5 years = 1 tyre/year per car — but replaced as a set of 4, so 4 tyres every 5 years = 0.8 tyres/car/year average).`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Total cars in India`,body:`Urban High (10.5cr × 30% × 95% × 1 car/HH) = 3.0M. Urban Middle (10.5cr × 50% × 60%) = 3.15M. Urban Low: 0. Rural High (19.6cr × 15% × 80% × 1) = 2.35M. Rural Middle (19.6cr × 35% × 10%) = 0.69M.
Total cars ≈ 9.2M + say 5M (2 cars for high income HHs) = ~14M cars.
Rounding: approximately 100 million (10 crore) cars in India (accounting for commercial vehicles and a growing base).`,result:`~10 crore 4-wheelers (passenger)`},{heading:`Step 2: New car tyres (replacement + new vehicles)`,body:`Annual new car sales ~4 million (2.5% of fleet).
4 million new cars × 5 tyres = 20 million new tyres.`,result:`20M tyres from new cars`},{heading:`Step 3: Replacement tyres on existing fleet`,body:`Existing fleet: 96 million cars × 4 operational tyres ÷ 5-year life
= 96M × 0.8 tyres/car/year ≈ 77 million replacement tyres.
Note: 1 spare tyre replaced less frequently → add 96M × 0.1 = 9.6M.`,result:`~87M replacement tyres`},{heading:`Step 4: Total tyre market`,body:`Total = 20M (new cars) + 87M (replacement) = 107M ≈ 100–110 million tyres/year.
In value terms: 100M tyres × Rs 3,500 average = Rs 35,000 crore.`,result:`~100–110 million tyres/year`}],answer:`The Indian 4-wheeler tyre market is approximately 100–110 million units per year.`,insight:`India's tyre industry body (ATMA) reports total tyre production of ~200 million units per year across all vehicle categories. The 4-wheeler passenger segment represents roughly 50–55% of units, consistent with our estimate of 100–110 million.`},
  {id:16,title:`Wine Bottles Consumed in India Per Week`,question:`Estimate the number of bottles of wine consumed in India per week.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Identify wine-drinking adults in India, estimate average weekly consumption, and divide by bottle size.`,assumptions:[`Wine is primarily consumed in urban India, specifically by working adults in the middle and high income brackets.`,`Urban population: 140 crore × 40% = 56 crore. Working adults (19–65 years): 70% = 39.2 crore.`,`Alcohol consumption rate among urban adults: Low income 40% drink, Middle income 70%, High income 90%.`,`Income split of urban working adults: Low 40%, Middle 40%, High 20%.`,`Wine's share among alcohol drinkers: In India, wine penetration is low (spirits and beer dominate). Wine share: 5% of Low income drinkers, 15% of Middle, 40% of High income.`,`Average glasses of wine per week among wine drinkers: 2 glasses. Standard wine bottle = 8 glasses.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Urban working adults by income`,body:`Total: 39.2 crore.
Low (40%) = 15.7cr; Middle (40%) = 15.7cr; High (20%) = 7.8cr.`,result:`39.2 crore urban working adults`},{heading:`Step 2: Wine drinkers by segment`,body:`Low: 15.7cr × 40% alcohol × 5% wine = 31.4 lakh.
Middle: 15.7cr × 70% alcohol × 15% wine = 164.8 lakh.
High: 7.8cr × 90% alcohol × 40% wine = 280.8 lakh.
Total wine drinkers = 477 lakh ≈ 4.8 crore wine drinkers.`,result:`~4.8 crore wine drinkers`},{heading:`Step 3: Weekly bottles consumed`,body:`Total glasses/week = 4.8 crore × 2 glasses = 9.6 crore glasses.
Bottles = 9.6 crore ÷ 8 glasses per bottle = 1.2 crore bottles/week.`,result:`~1.2 crore bottles/week`}],answer:`Approximately 1–1.5 crore bottles of wine are consumed in India per week.`,insight:`Sanity check: India's wine market is reported at ~2 crore cases per year (industry data 2023). 1 case = 12 bottles = 24 crore bottles/year = 46 lakh bottles/week. Our estimate of 1.2 crore/week appears high — the gap suggests our wine penetration rates are optimistic. A more conservative 5-10% of middle-income drinkers choosing wine gives ~50-60 lakh bottles/week, closer to industry data.`},
  {id:17,title:`Daily Sales of 1L Packaged Water in Delhi`,question:`Estimate the daily number of 1-litre packaged drinking water bottles sold in Delhi.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Split demand into tourist/transient buyers and regular retail consumers; estimate daily purchase rate for each.`,assumptions:[`Delhi population: 2 crore (20 million). Daily visitor and transient population: ~5 lakh.`,`Regular consumers of packaged water are mainly middle and high income households and offices.`,`Household penetration: High income (25% of Delhi) → 80% buy bottled water; Middle income (55%) → 30%.`,`Household size: 4. One 1L bottle purchased per household per day (shared or for specific use).`,`Restaurants and food establishments (~5 lakh in Delhi): 20% use bottled water at 2 bottles/day.`,`Tourists (5 lakh/day): 60% buy at least one 1L bottle.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Household demand`,body:`Delhi households = 20M ÷ 4 = 50 lakh.
High income (25%) = 12.5L HH × 80% = 10L households → 10 lakh bottles/day.
Middle income (55%) = 27.5L HH × 30% = 8.25L households → 8.25 lakh bottles/day.
Household total = 18.25 lakh ≈ 18 lakh bottles/day.`,result:`18 lakh bottles/day (household)`},{heading:`Step 2: Institutional and commercial demand`,body:`Food establishments: 5 lakh establishments × 20% = 1 lakh active buyers × 2 bottles = 2 lakh bottles/day.`,result:`2 lakh bottles/day (commercial)`},{heading:`Step 3: Tourist and transient demand`,body:`5 lakh daily visitors × 60% = 3 lakh buyers × 1 bottle = 3 lakh bottles/day.`,result:`3 lakh bottles/day (transient)`},{heading:`Step 4: Total`,body:`Total = 18L + 2L + 3L = 23 lakh ≈ 22–25 lakh 1L bottles per day.`,result:`~22–25 lakh bottles/day`}],answer:`Approximately 22–25 lakh 1-litre packaged water bottles are sold in Delhi per day.`,insight:`Sanity check: Delhi's packaged water market is estimated at ~Rs 1,000 crore annually. At Rs 20/litre bottle, that implies 500 million bottles/year = 137 lakh/day. Our estimate of 23 lakh seems conservative — the gap likely reflects that many consumers buy smaller (200ml, 500ml) pack sizes, and the Rs 1,000 crore figure includes all SKUs.`},
  {id:18,title:`Hand Sanitizer Consumption in Delhi Per Month`,question:`Estimate the quantity of hand sanitizer consumed in Delhi in a month (in litres).`,difficulty:`Easy`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Estimate the number of households that regularly use sanitizer, multiply by average monthly consumption per household.`,assumptions:[`Delhi population: 2 crore. Average household size: 4 → 50 lakh households.`,`Sanitizer penetration by income: BPL (10%) 0%, Low (30%) 30%, Middle (40%) 60%, High (20%) 100%.`,`Average monthly sanitizer consumption per household that uses it: 100 ml (approx. 1 standard 100ml bottle).`,`Institutional use (offices, hospitals, schools): estimated at 30% of household demand.`,`Only personal-use liquid sanitizer is counted.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Households by income and penetration`,body:`Total households: 50 lakh.
BPL (10% = 5L) × 0% = 0.
Low income (30% = 15L) × 30% = 4.5L households.
Middle income (40% = 20L) × 60% = 12L households.
High income (20% = 10L) × 100% = 10L households.
Total households using sanitizer = 26.5 lakh.`,result:`26.5 lakh using households`},{heading:`Step 2: Monthly household consumption`,body:`26.5 lakh households × 100 ml = 265 lakh × 100 ml = 26.5 crore ml = 2.65 lakh litres.`,result:`2.65 lakh litres (household)`},{heading:`Step 3: Adding institutional use`,body:`Institutional = 30% of household = 0.30 × 2.65 lakh = 0.80 lakh litres.`,result:`0.80 lakh litres (institutional)`},{heading:`Step 4: Total monthly consumption`,body:`Total = 2.65L + 0.80L = 3.45 lakh litres ≈ 3.5 lakh litres per month.`,result:`~3.5 lakh litres/month`}],answer:`Delhi consumes approximately 3–4 lakh litres of hand sanitizer per month.`,insight:`Context: During peak COVID periods (2020-21), sanitizer demand was 5–8× higher. Post-pandemic normalisation has brought consumption down; this estimate reflects current (normal) usage patterns.`},
  {id:19,title:`BCom(H) Admissions at Delhi University Per Year`,question:`Estimate the total number of BCom (Honours) admissions at Delhi University in a year.`,difficulty:`Easy`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Estimate from the number of DU colleges offering BCom(H), their tier, average seats per tier, and typical vacancy rates.`,assumptions:[`Delhi University has approximately 80 affiliated colleges, of which ~70% offer BCom(H) = 56 colleges.`,`Colleges are categorised in three tiers: Tier 1 (high-reputation; ~30%), Tier 2 (mid-tier; ~40%), Tier 3 (lower-rank; ~30%).`,`Tier 1: 17 colleges × 500 total BCom seats × 80% BCom(H) share × 95% fill rate.`,`Tier 2: 22 colleges × 500 seats × 60% BCom(H) share × 85% fill rate.`,`Tier 3: 17 colleges × 500 seats × 40% BCom(H) share × 80% fill rate.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Tier 1 colleges`,body:`17 colleges × 500 seats × 80% BCom(H) × 95% filled
= 17 × 400 × 0.95 = 6,460 students.`,result:`6,460 Tier 1 admissions`},{heading:`Step 2: Tier 2 colleges`,body:`22 colleges × 500 seats × 60% BCom(H) × 85% filled
= 22 × 300 × 0.85 = 5,610 students.`,result:`5,610 Tier 2 admissions`},{heading:`Step 3: Tier 3 colleges`,body:`17 colleges × 500 seats × 40% BCom(H) × 80% filled
= 17 × 200 × 0.80 = 2,720 students.`,result:`2,720 Tier 3 admissions`},{heading:`Step 4: Total`,body:`Total BCom(H) admissions = 6,460 + 5,610 + 2,720 = 14,790 ≈ 14,500–15,000 students.`,result:`~14,500–15,000 students/year`}],answer:`Delhi University admits approximately 14,000–15,000 students in BCom (Honours) per year.`,insight:`DU's official Common Seat Allocation System shows approximately 15,000–18,000 BCom(H) seats across affiliated colleges. Our estimate of ~15,000 is well-aligned.`},
  {id:20,title:`Credit Cards Issued in Delhi Per Year`,question:`Estimate the number of new credit cards issued in Delhi in a year.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Identify the creditworthy population in Delhi, determine current card ownership, and divide by average card life to get annual issuances.`,assumptions:[`Delhi population: 2 crore. Average household size: 4 → 50 lakh households.`,`Urban (70% of Delhi): 35 lakh households. Rural (30%): 15 lakh.`,`Credit card eligibility (typically middle income and above):
  Urban High income (25%): 8.75L HH × 95% eligible = 8.3L.
  Urban Middle income (55%): 19.25L HH × 50% eligible = 9.6L.
  Rural High (15%): 2.25L HH × 100% = 2.25L.
  Others: negligible.`,`1 card per eligible household (primary cardholder basis; not counting supplementary cards).`,`Average card validity: 3 years → annual renewal/new issuance = total cards ÷ 3.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Total credit card-holding households`,body:`Urban High: 8.3 lakh.
Urban Middle: 9.6 lakh.
Rural High: 2.25 lakh.
Total: 20.15 lakh credit card holders.`,result:`~20 lakh cardholding households`},{heading:`Step 2: Annual card issuances`,body:`Annual issuances = 20 lakh ÷ 3 years = 6.67 lakh ≈ 7 lakh cards/year.
(This covers both renewals and new issuances.)`,result:`~7 lakh cards/year`}],answer:`Approximately 7 lakh credit cards are issued in Delhi per year.`,insight:`Cross-check: RBI data shows India has ~80 million credit cards total, issued at a rate of ~10–15 million per year nationwide. Delhi accounts for roughly 8–10% of India's credit card base, implying ~10–15 lakh issuances/year. Our estimate of 7 lakh appears slightly conservative — the gap reflects our exclusion of supplementary cards and new-to-credit young professionals.`},
  {id:21,title:`Revenue of a Fantasy Sports Platform in Year 1`,question:`Estimate the total revenue a leading fantasy sports platform can generate in its first year in India.`,difficulty:`Hard`,category:`Revenue Estimation`,approach:`Build a funnel from India's cricket-watching population to fantasy sports players, estimate betting frequency and average value, then apply platform commission.`,assumptions:[`Focus on cricket (70% of fantasy sports revenue); other sports extrapolated at the end.`,`Urban population in India: ~56 crore. Working-age adults (18–40): ~40% = 22.4 crore.`,`Gender: Males dominate cricket viewership and fantasy sports participation. Male working-age urban adults: ~11 crore.`,`Sports viewership rate: 60% of urban males watch cricket = 6.6 crore viewers.`,`Digital payment users among viewers: 70% = 4.62 crore.`,`Fantasy sports participation rate (first year, early adoption): 20% = 0.92 crore players.`,`Player segmentation by activity: High frequency (10%) 60 bets/year; Medium (30%) 48 bets/year; Low (60%) 18 bets/year.`,`Average bet value: High Rs 500, Medium Rs 250, Low Rs 100.`,`Platform takes 15–20% commission on winnings; effective gross margin on transaction value: ~10%.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Fantasy sports player base`,body:`0.92 crore players for cricket.
High (10%) = 9.2L; Medium (30%) = 27.6L; Low (60%) = 55.2L.`,result:`92 lakh cricket fantasy players`},{heading:`Step 2: Annual bets and transaction value`,body:`High: 9.2L × 60 bets × Rs 500 = Rs 2,760 crore.
Medium: 27.6L × 48 bets × Rs 250 = Rs 3,312 crore.
Low: 55.2L × 18 bets × Rs 100 = Rs 994 crore.
Total cricket transaction value = Rs 7,066 crore.`,result:`Rs 7,066 crore in cricket transactions`},{heading:`Step 3: Platform revenue from cricket`,body:`Platform's gross revenue = 10% of transaction value = Rs 706 crore from cricket.`,result:`Rs 706 crore (cricket)`},{heading:`Step 4: Adjusting for all sports (cricket = 70%)`,body:`Total platform revenue = Rs 706 crore ÷ 70% = Rs 1,008 crore ≈ Rs 1,000 crore.`,result:`~Rs 1,000 crore in Year 1`}],answer:`A leading fantasy sports platform can target approximately Rs 800–1,200 crore in Year 1 revenue.`,insight:`India's largest fantasy sports platforms have reported revenues exceeding Rs 2,000 crore annually after achieving market maturity over several years. Year-1 revenue for a well-funded new entrant would realistically fall in the Rs 200–500 crore range, depending on marketing investment. Our Rs 1,000 crore estimate represents the optimistic upper bound for a strong launch.`},
  {id:22,title:`Earnings of a Pickpocket in a Busy Market`,question:`Estimate the daily earnings of a pickpocket operating in a busy market area in a metropolitan city.`,difficulty:`Easy`,category:`Revenue Estimation`,approach:`Estimate the total footfall in the market, filter to identify viable targets, apply success rate per attempt, and multiply by average wallet value.`,assumptions:[`The pickpocket operates in a busy urban market (like a large bazaar) during peak hours: 10 am to 9 pm (11 hours).`,`The market has approximately 150 shops. Each shop sees 10 customers/hour in off-peak and 20 in peak hours.`,`Average visits per customer = 3 shops → total unique footfall = (shops × customers/hr × hours) ÷ avg shops visited.`,`70% of visitors enter shops; 30% are passers-by.`,`Of those in shops, 60% carry a wallet (others use cards or have no cash).`,`Of wallet carriers, the pickpocket attempts 3% as viable targets.`,`Success rate per attempt: 10%.`,`Average wallet value: Rs 500.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Total footfall in the market`,body:`Peak hours (11 am–9 pm, 10 hrs): 150 shops × 20 customers/hr ÷ 3 shops/visit = 1,000 unique customers/hr.
Off-peak (10–11 am, 1 hr): 150 × 10 ÷ 3 = 500 customers/hr.
Total daily footfall = 1,000 × 10 + 500 × 1 = 10,500 ≈ 10,000 people.`,result:`~10,000 people in the market`},{heading:`Step 2: Viable pickpocket targets`,body:`In-shop visitors: 10,000 × 70% = 7,000.
Wallet carriers: 7,000 × 60% = 4,200.
Viable targets (3% of wallet carriers): 4,200 × 3% = 126 ≈ 125 targets.`,result:`~125 viable targets`},{heading:`Step 3: Daily earnings`,body:`Successful pickpockets = 125 × 10% success rate = 12.5 ≈ 12 attempts succeed.
Daily earnings = 12 × Rs 500 = Rs 6,000.`,result:`Rs 6,000/day`}],answer:`A pickpocket in a busy urban market can earn approximately Rs 5,000–7,000 per day.`,insight:`This is an unconventional guesstimate designed to test structured thinking under ambiguity. The key insight is to break the problem into a clear funnel: footfall → viable targets → successful attempts → earnings. The interviewer is testing whether the candidate builds the framework logically, not whether the final number is precise.`},
  {id:23,title:`Number of Movie Screens in Delhi`,question:`Estimate the number of movie screens in Delhi.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Estimate the number of moviegoers per month, calculate screens needed based on average screen capacity and occupancy.`,assumptions:[`Delhi population: 2 crore. Income split: Low 25%, Middle 45%, High 30%.`,`Moviegoing frequency per month: Low income casual watchers 10% of population × 1 visit; Middle income 25% × 1 visit + 10% movie buffs × 4 visits; High income 25% × 1 visit + 10% buffs × 4 visits.`,`Each screen has 300 seats, 5 shows per day (3 weekday, 5 weekend — blended average).`,`Weekday occupancy: 60%; Weekend occupancy: 90%. Days: 22 weekdays, 8 weekend days/month.`,`Monthly screen capacity = (300 × 3 shows × 22 days × 60%) + (300 × 5 shows × 8 days × 90%).`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Monthly moviegoing audience`,body:`Low income (50L people) × [10% × 1 visit] = 5L visits.
Middle income (90L) × [25% × 1 + 10% × 4] = 90L × 65% = 58.5L visits.
High income (60L) × [25% × 1 + 10% × 4] = 60L × 65% = 39L visits.
Total monthly visits = 5 + 58.5 + 39 = 102.5 lakh ≈ 1 crore visits.`,result:`~1 crore visits/month`},{heading:`Step 2: Monthly capacity of one screen`,body:`Weekday capacity: 300 seats × 3 shows × 22 days × 60% = 11,880 seats/month.
Weekend capacity: 300 × 5 × 8 × 90% = 10,800 seats/month.
Total per screen = 22,680 ≈ 22,000–23,000 seats/month.`,result:`~23,000 seats/screen/month`},{heading:`Step 3: Number of screens`,body:`Screens = Total monthly visits ÷ Capacity per screen
= 1,00,00,000 ÷ 23,000 = 435 ≈ 430–450 screens.`,result:`~430–450 screens`}],answer:`Delhi has approximately 400–450 movie screens.`,insight:`Delhi's actual screen count is approximately 450–500 screens across multiplexes (PVR, Inox, Cinepolis) and standalone cinemas. Our estimate of 430–450 is closely aligned.`},
  {id:24,title:`Petrol Consumed Per Day in Delhi-NCR`,question:`Estimate the volume of petrol consumed per day in Delhi-NCR for personal transportation.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Calculate the number of petrol-powered vehicles by type, multiply by average daily distance, and divide by fuel efficiency.`,assumptions:[`Delhi-NCR population: 2 crore. Average household size: 5 → 40 lakh households.`,`Vehicles per household by income: BPL 0, Low 0.5 two-wheelers, Middle 1 two-wheeler + 1 four-wheeler, High 1.5 two-wheelers + 2 four-wheelers.`,`Income split of NCR households: BPL 20% = 8L HH, Low 30% = 12L HH, Middle 25% = 10L HH, High 5% = 2L HH (remainder are lower-middle, approximated into Low).`,`Average daily distance: Two-wheelers 20 km, Four-wheelers 20 km.`,`Fuel efficiency: Two-wheeler 50 km/litre; Four-wheeler (petrol) 12 km/litre.`,`20% of 4-wheelers run on CNG or diesel (not petrol); only 80% of 4-wheelers counted.`,`10% additional fuel consumed by non-NCR residents passing through.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Two-wheelers and petrol consumed`,body:`Low HH (12L × 0.5) = 6L. Middle (10L × 1) = 10L. High (2L × 1.5) = 3L.
Total two-wheelers = 19 lakh.
Daily petrol = 19L vehicles × 20 km ÷ 50 km/litre = 7.6 lakh litres.`,result:`7.6 lakh litres (2-wheelers)`},{heading:`Step 2: Four-wheelers and petrol consumed`,body:`Middle (10L × 1) = 10L. High (2L × 2) = 4L. Total = 14 lakh 4-wheelers.
80% are petrol = 11.2 lakh petrol cars.
Daily petrol = 11.2L × 20 km ÷ 12 km/litre = 18.7 lakh litres.`,result:`18.7 lakh litres (4-wheelers)`},{heading:`Step 3: Total petrol consumption`,body:`Total (residents) = 7.6L + 18.7L = 26.3 lakh litres.
+ 10% for non-residents = 26.3L × 1.1 = 28.9 lakh litres.
≈ 29 lakh litres per day.`,result:`~29 lakh litres/day`}],answer:`Delhi-NCR consumes approximately 28–32 lakh litres of petrol per day for personal transportation.`,insight:`Delhi's petroleum ministry data shows daily fuel sales of ~35–40 lakh litres (all fuel types) at Delhi's fuel stations, of which petrol accounts for roughly 60–65%, giving ~23–26 lakh litres. Our estimate of ~29 lakh is in a consistent range.`},
  {id:25,title:`Food Delivery App — Active Delivery Partners in Mumbai`,question:`Estimate the number of active delivery partners for a major food delivery app (like Swiggy or Zomato) in Mumbai.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Estimate daily orders for the platform in Mumbai, then divide by orders delivered per partner per day.`,assumptions:[`Mumbai population: 2 crore. Smartphone internet users: ~70% = 1.4 crore.`,`Online food delivery users: 35% of internet users = 49 lakh active users.`,`Platform market share (major app): 45% = 22 lakh users.`,`Average order frequency: 1.5 orders/week per active user = 22L × 1.5 ÷ 7 = 4.7 lakh orders/day.`,`Peak hours (12–2 pm and 7–10 pm) account for ~60% of orders. Order during peak = 2.82 lakh; Off-peak = 1.88 lakh.`,`During peak, one delivery partner can complete 2 deliveries per hour (30 min round trip).`,`Each partner works ~5 hours of peak time and ~3 hours off-peak per day.`,`Deliveries per partner/day: (5 hrs × 2/hr) + (3 hrs × 1.5/hr) = 10 + 4.5 = 14.5 ≈ 14 deliveries.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Daily orders for the platform in Mumbai`,body:`22 lakh active users × 1.5 orders/week ÷ 7 days = 4.7 lakh orders/day.`,result:`4.7 lakh orders/day`},{heading:`Step 2: Deliveries per partner per day`,body:`Peak (5 hrs × 2 deliveries/hr) + Off-peak (3 hrs × 1.5/hr)
= 10 + 4.5 = 14.5 ≈ 14 deliveries per partner per day.`,result:`14 deliveries/partner/day`},{heading:`Step 3: Number of active partners`,body:`Active partners = Total daily orders ÷ Deliveries per partner
= 4,70,000 ÷ 14 = 33,571 ≈ 33,000–35,000.
Adjusting for ~20% idle/part-time partners (not on shift at any given time):
Registered partners = 33,000 ÷ 0.80 = ~41,000.`,result:`~35,000–40,000 active partners`}],answer:`Approximately 35,000–40,000 delivery partners are active for a major food delivery app in Mumbai.`,insight:`Swiggy publicly reported ~300,000 delivery partners across India in 2022. Mumbai's share (~10% of India's delivery volume) would imply ~30,000 partners — closely matching our estimate.`},
  {id:26,title:`Daily Passengers on a High-Frequency Metro Corridor`,question:`Estimate the number of daily passengers on a high-frequency metro rail corridor in a major Indian city, running approximately 18 hours per day.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Supply-side approach: trains per hour × coaches × capacity × occupancy rate, modelled across peak, medium, and off-peak time bands for a weekday.`,assumptions:[`The metro corridor operates 18 hours per day (5:30 am to 11:30 pm).`,`Train composition: 6 coaches per train; capacity 300 passengers per train.`,`Train frequency: Peak hours (6 hrs): 1 train/minute; Medium hours (7 hrs): 1 train/90 sec; Off-peak (5 hrs): 1 train/2 min.`,`Occupancy rates: Peak 150% (standing passengers included), Medium 100%, Off-peak 40%.`,`Ridership is counted as unique trips (one entry per journey).`,`Weekday ridership is modelled; weekends are approximately 70% of weekday volume.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Passengers during peak hours (one direction)`,body:`60 trains/hr × 6 hrs = 360 trains.
360 trains × 300 passengers/train × 150% occupancy = 1,62,000 passengers.`,result:`1,62,000 peak passengers`},{heading:`Step 2: Medium hours`,body:`40 trains/hr × 7 hrs = 280 trains.
280 × 300 × 100% = 84,000 passengers.`,result:`84,000 medium-hours passengers`},{heading:`Step 3: Off-peak hours`,body:`30 trains/hr × 5 hrs = 150 trains.
150 × 300 × 40% = 18,000 passengers.`,result:`18,000 off-peak passengers`},{heading:`Step 4: Total daily (both directions)`,body:`One direction: 1,62,000 + 84,000 + 18,000 = 2,64,000.
Both directions (multiply by 2, but passenger double-counted as they only travel one leg): Each unique trip = 1 entry.
Approximately: 2,64,000 unique trips per day (one way) — this is the ridership count.
Weekday adjusted average: 100%. Final estimate ≈ 2,60,000–3,00,000 passengers per day.`,result:`~3 lakh passengers/day`}],answer:`The Delhi Metro this metro corridor carries approximately 3 lakh passengers on a typical weekday.`,insight:`High-frequency metro corridors in major Indian cities like Delhi, Mumbai, and Bengaluru typically record 3–5 lakh daily riders on their busiest lines. Our estimate of ~3 lakh is consistent with published data for busy metro corridors. The three-hour peak window drives over 60% of daily ridership.`},
  {id:27,title:`Daily Distance by Quick-Commerce Drivers in Delhi`,question:`Estimate the total daily distance covered by quick-commerce delivery riders in Delhi.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Estimate the number of daily orders placed via quick-commerce in Delhi, apply a target platform's market share, and multiply by average delivery distance.`,assumptions:[`Delhi population: 2 crore. Average household size: 4 → 50 lakh households.`,`Serviceable area: Quick-commerce covers approximately 70% of Delhi = 35 lakh households.`,`Income segments: Low (20%) 7L HH, Middle (50%) 17.5L HH, High (20%) 7L HH. (BPL excluded as non-users.)`,`Quick-commerce adoption rate: Low 0%, Middle 60%, High 90%.`,`Eligible user households = 17.5L × 60% + 7L × 90% = 10.5L + 6.3L = 16.8 lakh.`,`Order frequency per week: Frequent users (30%) 3 orders/week; Normal (30%) 2 orders/week; Rare (40%) 1 order/week.`,`Target platform market share: 20%.`,`Average delivery distance per order: 2 km (dark store to customer) + 1 km return ≈ 3 km net riding per order.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Total weekly quick-commerce orders in Delhi`,body:`Frequent (30% of 16.8L = 5.04L) × 3/wk = 15.1L orders.
Normal (30% = 5.04L) × 2/wk = 10.1L orders.
Rare (40% = 6.72L) × 1/wk = 6.7L orders.
Total weekly orders = 31.9 lakh.
Daily orders = 31.9L ÷ 7 = 4.56 lakh ≈ 4.5 lakh orders/day.`,result:`4.5 lakh orders/day (total market)`},{heading:`Step 2: Target platform's daily orders`,body:`Platform market share 20%: 4.5L × 20% = 90,000 orders/day.`,result:`90,000 orders/day`},{heading:`Step 3: Daily distance by platform's riders`,body:`Total distance = 90,000 orders × 5 km (round trip per order, including dark store to customer and back)
= 4,50,000 km = 4.5 lakh km/day.`,result:`~4.5 lakh km/day`}],answer:`Quick-commerce delivery riders for a major platform cover approximately 4–5 lakh km per day in Delhi.`,insight:`Sanity check: If the platform has ~5,000 active riders in Delhi, each rider would cover 4,50,000 ÷ 5,000 = 90 km per day — reasonable for someone doing ~18 deliveries at 5 km each.`},
  {id:28,title:`Mutual Fund Market Size in India`,question:`Estimate the total market size of the mutual fund industry in India (retail Assets Under Management).`,difficulty:`Hard`,category:`Market Sizing`,approach:`Segment the investable population by income and geography, estimate savings rates and portfolio allocation to mutual funds, and aggregate.`,assumptions:[`India's population: 140 crore. Urban: 42 crore (30%), Rural: 98 crore (70%).`,`Urban income split: High 25% (10.5cr), Middle 55% (23.1cr), Low 20% (8.4cr).`,`Rural income split: High 15% (14.7cr), Middle 35% (34.3cr), Low 50% (49cr).`,`Average annual household income: Urban High Rs 20L, Urban Middle Rs 5L, Rural High Rs 15L, Rural Middle Rs 5L.`,`Savings rate: 50% for High income, 40% for Middle, 20% for Low.`,`% of savings allocated to riskier investments (MF eligible): Urban High 70%, Urban Middle 50%, Rural High 10%, Rural Middle 5%.`,`Average household size: 4 (urban), 5 (rural). Convert population to households.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Urban high income MF investment`,body:`Households: 10.5cr ÷ 4 = 2.625 crore.
Annual savings: 2.625cr × Rs 20L × 50% = Rs 262,500 crore.
Invested in MF (70%): Rs 183,750 crore.`,result:`Rs 1,83,750 crore`},{heading:`Step 2: Urban middle income MF investment`,body:`Households: 23.1cr ÷ 4 = 5.775 crore.
Savings: 5.775cr × Rs 5L × 40% = Rs 1,15,500 crore.
In MF (50%): Rs 57,750 crore.`,result:`Rs 57,750 crore`},{heading:`Step 3: Rural high income MF investment`,body:`Households: 14.7cr ÷ 5 = 2.94 crore.
Savings: 2.94cr × Rs 15L × 50% = Rs 2,20,500 crore.
In MF (10%): Rs 22,050 crore.`,result:`Rs 22,050 crore`},{heading:`Step 4: Rural middle income MF investment`,body:`Households: 34.3cr ÷ 5 = 6.86 crore.
Savings: 6.86cr × Rs 5L × 40% = Rs 1,37,200 crore.
In MF (5%): Rs 6,860 crore.`,result:`Rs 6,860 crore`},{heading:`Step 5: Total MF AUM`,body:`Total = Rs 1,83,750 + 57,750 + 22,050 + 6,860 = Rs 2,70,410 crore ≈ Rs 2.7 lakh crore.`,result:`Rs ~2.7 lakh crore AUM`}],answer:`India's retail mutual fund market is approximately Rs 2.5–3 lakh crore in AUM.`,insight:`AMFI data shows total industry AUM of Rs 50+ lakh crore in 2024. However, a significant portion is institutional (corporate treasuries, HNIs). Retail AUM (SIPs, small investors) is approximately Rs 20–25 lakh crore. Our estimate of Rs 2.7 lakh crore is therefore conservative — primarily because we model only annual new investment flows, not the accumulated stock of existing investments.`},
  {id:29,title:`Number of Car Tyres in Delhi`,question:`Estimate the total number of car tyres (including spare tyres) currently in Delhi.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Estimate the number of passenger cars in Delhi by income segment, then multiply by 5 tyres per car.`,assumptions:[`Delhi population: 3 crore (including NCR fringe, for car count). Average household size: 4 → 75 lakh households.`,`Income segments: Middle income 45% = 33.75L HH, High income 15% = 11.25L HH. (Low and BPL have negligible car ownership.)`,`Middle income sub-segments: Lower middle 70% of middle income → 0.4 cars/HH; Upper middle 30% → 0.8 cars/HH.`,`High income sub-segments: Upper class 90% → 1.8 cars/HH; HNI 10% → 3 cars/HH.`,`Each car has 5 tyres (4 road + 1 spare).`,`Taxis/commercial vehicles (app-based, radio cabs): assume 10% of private car owners use taxis, adding ~1 lakh additional cabs.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Cars owned by middle income households`,body:`Lower middle (70% of 33.75L = 23.6L HH) × 0.4 = 9.45 lakh cars.
Upper middle (30% of 33.75L = 10.1L HH) × 0.8 = 8.1 lakh cars.
Middle income cars = 17.6 lakh.`,result:`17.6 lakh cars`},{heading:`Step 2: Cars owned by high income households`,body:`Upper class (90% of 11.25L = 10.1L HH) × 1.8 = 18.2 lakh cars.
HNI (10% of 11.25L = 1.1L HH) × 3 = 3.4 lakh cars.
High income cars = 21.6 lakh.`,result:`21.6 lakh cars`},{heading:`Step 3: Total cars and tyres`,body:`Total private cars = 17.6L + 21.6L = 39.2 lakh cars.
Add ~1 lakh commercial taxis = 40.2 lakh cars.
Total tyres = 40.2 lakh × 5 = 201 lakh ≈ 2 crore tyres.`,result:`~2 crore tyres in Delhi`}],answer:`Delhi has approximately 2 crore car tyres in circulation.`,insight:`Delhi's registered vehicles stood at ~1.1 crore as of 2023 (VAHAN data), of which ~40 lakh are cars/jeeps/SUVs — consistent with our estimate of ~40 lakh cars. At 5 tyres each, our total of 2 crore tyres is well-aligned.`},
  {id:30,title:`ATM Withdrawals in a Tier-2 Indian City Per Month`,question:`Estimate the number of ATM withdrawals made in a typical Tier-2 Indian city in a month.`,difficulty:`Easy`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Start with city population, filter to the banked population, then to ATM users, and multiply by withdrawal frequency.`,assumptions:[`A Tier-2 Indian city (e.g., Lucknow, Indore, Kochi) has a population of approximately 20 lakh.`,`Age segments: 0–14 years (25%): minors, excluded. 15–24 years (18%): partial banking access. 25–54 years (40%): primary working population. 55–64 years (10%): still active bankers. 65+ years (7%): low ATM usage.`,`Banking penetration by age: 15–24: 40% banked; 25–54: 90% banked; 55–64: 80% banked; 65+: 60% banked.`,`ATM usage rate (among banked): 15–24: 50%; 25–54: 75%; 55–64: 40%; 65+: 20%.`,`Monthly withdrawal frequency: 15–24: 1.5 times; 25–54: 2.5 times; 55–64: 2 times; 65+: 1 time.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Banked population by age segment`,body:`15–24 (3.6L) × 40% = 1.44L banked.
25–54 (8L) × 90% = 7.2L banked.
55–64 (2L) × 80% = 1.6L banked.
65+ (1.4L) × 60% = 0.84L banked.`,result:`11.08 lakh banked persons`},{heading:`Step 2: ATM users`,body:`15–24: 1.44L × 50% = 0.72L.
25–54: 7.2L × 75% = 5.4L.
55–64: 1.6L × 40% = 0.64L.
65+: 0.84L × 20% = 0.17L.`,result:`6.93 lakh ATM users`},{heading:`Step 3: Monthly withdrawals`,body:`15–24: 0.72L × 1.5 = 1.08L.
25–54: 5.4L × 2.5 = 13.5L.
55–64: 0.64L × 2.0 = 1.28L.
65+: 0.17L × 1.0 = 0.17L.
Total = 16.03 lakh ≈ 16 lakh withdrawals/month.`,result:`~16 lakh withdrawals/month`}],answer:`A Tier-2 Indian city of 20 lakh population sees approximately 15–17 lakh ATM withdrawals per month.`,insight:`This implies ~800–900 withdrawals per ATM per month if the city has ~1,800 ATMs (typical for a Tier-2 city at 1 ATM per 1,000 population). RBI data shows average ATM throughput of 600–1,200 transactions per machine per month — our estimate is consistent.`},
  {id:31,title:`Dog Food Consumed in India Annually`,question:`Estimate the total amount of commercial dog food consumed in India per year (in kilograms).`,difficulty:`Easy`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Estimate the number of pet dogs in India, segment by size, and multiply by annual consumption per size category.`,assumptions:[`India's total population: 140 crore; average household size 4.5 → ~31 crore households.`,`Dog ownership is concentrated in upper-middle and high income segments (for commercial packaged food).`,`Upper-middle income (15% of households = 4.65 crore HH): 12% own a dog = 0.56 crore dogs.`,`High income (5% = 1.55 crore HH): 25% own a dog = 0.39 crore dogs.`,`Low and middle income households that own dogs primarily feed them home food — excluded from commercial food estimate.`,`Dog size distribution among pet dogs: Small (50%), Medium (30%), Large (15%), Giant (5%).`,`Annual commercial food consumption: Small 55 kg, Medium 110 kg, Large 180 kg, Giant 250 kg.`,`Weighted average = 0.5×55 + 0.3×110 + 0.15×180 + 0.05×250 = 27.5+33+27+12.5 = 100 kg/dog/year.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Total commercial pet dogs in India`,body:`Upper-middle: 0.56 crore dogs.
High income: 0.39 crore dogs.
Total: 0.95 crore ≈ 1 crore commercial pet dogs.`,result:`~1 crore commercial pet dogs`},{heading:`Step 2: Annual dog food consumption`,body:`Weighted average consumption: 100 kg/dog/year.
Total = 1 crore dogs × 100 kg = 100 crore kg = 100 lakh tonnes.`,result:`100 crore kg per year`}],answer:`Approximately 100 crore kg (1 million tonnes) of commercial dog food is consumed in India annually.`,insight:`India's pet food market was valued at Rs 800–1,000 crore in 2023 (Euromonitor, IMARC). At Rs 100 per kg average price, that implies 8–10 lakh tonnes of dog food — our estimate of ~1 million tonnes is in the right range. The market is growing rapidly at 15%+ CAGR as pet ownership rises in urban India.`},
  {id:32,title:`Daily Milk Production in an Eastern Indian State`,question:`Estimate the daily milk production in a mid-sized eastern Indian state with a population of approximately 4 crore and a significant rural agricultural base.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Supply-side approach: estimate the number of milch cattle owned by rural farming households in the state, apply a lactation rate and average yield per lactating animal.`,assumptions:[`State population: 4 crore. Average household size: 5 → 80 lakh households.`,`Urban (30%): 24 lakh households. Rural (70%): 56 lakh households.`,`Of rural households, agriculture-based: 65% = 36.4 lakh households.`,`Cattle ownership by income: Lower income (40%) 1 cow/family; Middle income (40%) 3 cows/family; Upper income (10%) 8 cows/family.`,`Only cows are counted for milk estimation (buffaloes excluded for simplicity).`,`Average milk yield per lactating cow: 4.5 litres/day.`,`Lactation rate: 50% of cows are lactating at any given time.`,`The state has moderate organised dairy cooperative infrastructure (unlike Gujarat or Punjab).`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Number of cows in rural this eastern Indian state`,body:`Agricultural households: 36.4 lakh.
Lower income (40% = 14.56L HH) × 1 cow = 14.56 lakh cows.
Middle income (40% = 14.56L HH) × 3 cows = 43.68 lakh cows.
Upper income (10% = 3.64L HH) × 8 cows = 29.12 lakh cows.
Total cows = 87.36 lakh ≈ 88 lakh cows.`,result:`88 lakh cows`},{heading:`Step 2: Lactating cows`,body:`50% lactating at any given time = 88L × 50% = 44 lakh lactating cows.`,result:`44 lakh lactating cows`},{heading:`Step 3: Daily milk production`,body:`44 lakh lactating cows × 4.5 litres/cow/day = 198 lakh litres ≈ 2 crore litres per day.`,result:`~2 crore litres/day`}],answer:`an eastern Indian state produces approximately 1.8–2 crore litres of milk per day.`,insight:`Eastern Indian states with comparable demographic profiles typically report daily milk production of 15–20 lakh litres. Our estimate of approximately 2 crore litres is slightly high, likely because we assumed 3 cows per middle-income farming family — 2 cows is a more realistic average. Adjusting that assumption brings the estimate closer to 1.5 crore litres/day.`},
  {id:33,title:`Hotel Room Nights at a Popular Coastal Tourist Destination During Peak Season`,question:`Estimate the number of hotel room nights booked at a popular Indian coastal tourist destination during its three-month peak season.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Estimate tourists visiting during the peak season, segment by income to determine average stay duration and room sharing, then calculate total room nights.`,assumptions:[`The destination receives approximately 8 million tourists annually.`,`Peak season (3 months) accounts for 40% of annual arrivals → 3.2 million peak-season tourists.`,`Income split: High income 10% (3.2L), Middle-high 60% (19.2L), Middle-low 30% (9.6L).`,`Average stay: High 7 nights, Middle-high 4 nights, Middle-low 3 nights.`,`Persons per room: High 1.5, Middle-high 2.0, Middle-low 3.0.`,`The destination is a well-established beach tourism market with a mix of hotels, resorts, and homestays.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Room nights by tourist segment`,body:`High income: 3.2L tourists × 7 nights ÷ 1.5 persons/room = 14.9 lakh room nights.
Middle-high: 19.2L × 4 nights ÷ 2 = 38.4 lakh room nights.
Middle-low: 9.6L × 3 nights ÷ 3 = 9.6 lakh room nights.`,result:`High 14.9L · Mid-H 38.4L · Mid-L 9.6L`},{heading:`Step 2: Total room nights`,body:`Total = 14.9 + 38.4 + 9.6 = 62.9 lakh ≈ 63 lakh room nights.`,result:`~63 lakh room nights`}],answer:`Approximately 60–65 lakh room nights are booked in the destination during the peak season (November–February).`,insight:`Popular Indian coastal destinations with 8 million annual visitors typically have 30,000–60,000 registered accommodation rooms. At 63 lakh room nights over 120 peak days, average occupancy = 63L ÷ 120 ÷ 50,000 rooms ≈ near 100% — consistent with a heavily-booked peak season at popular Indian beach destinations.`},
  {id:34,title:`Slow-Moving Vehicles at a Major Indian Airport`,question:`Estimate the number of slow-moving ground vehicles operating at a major Indian airport at any given point during peak hours.`,difficulty:`Hard`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Classify vehicle categories (passenger transport, baggage handling, cargo, fuel, miscellaneous), calculate required vehicles for each category based on flight and passenger volumes.`,assumptions:[`Major Indian airport (comparable to Delhi): ~400 total flights per day; ~200 flights during 12 peak hours.`,`3 active runways; peak hour: 4 flights per runway per hour = 12 landings per hour.`,`Each aircraft carries ~180 passengers on average. Flights/day: 288 at high, 72 at medium, 36 at low traffic hours.`,`80% of passengers check baggage; each baggage cart carries 100 bags.`,`Cargo: ~1 million tonnes per year through the airport = ~2,700 tonnes per day; cargo carriers at 0.5 tonnes/trip.`,`Refuelling vehicles: ~1 per 2 flights in peak hour.`,`Miscellaneous (crew buses, catering, cleaning, medical): ~10% of flight count vehicles.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Passenger transport carts`,body:`Peak hour: 12 landings × 180 passengers = 2,160 passengers.
Passengers needing assistance (elderly, wheelchair) = 5% = 108.
Transport carts at 12 passengers each = 108 ÷ 12 = 9 passenger carts.`,result:`9 passenger carts`},{heading:`Step 2: Baggage handling carts`,body:`2,160 passengers × 80% baggage = 1,728 bags.
Check-in closes 45 min before departure: 30 min for bag transfer = 6 round trips/cart.
Each cart carries 100 bags → 6 trips × 100 = 600 bags handled per cart.
1,728 ÷ 600 ≈ 3 carts active for arrivals. Plus departures (mirror): 6 baggage carts total.`,result:`~6 baggage carts`},{heading:`Step 3: Cargo vehicles`,body:`2,700 tonnes/day ÷ 12 peak hours = 225 tonnes/peak hour.
Cargo carrier capacity: 0.5 tonnes. Trips per vehicle per hour: 2.
225 ÷ (0.5 × 2) = 225 vehicles — this seems too high.
Actually: each carriage carries ~1.5 tonnes and makes 2 round trips/hr = 3 tonnes/vehicle/hr.
225 ÷ 3 = 75 cargo vehicles.`,result:`75 cargo vehicles`},{heading:`Step 4: Fuel and miscellaneous`,body:`Refuelling: 12 flights/hr ÷ 2 = 6 fuel tankers.
Miscellaneous (catering, cleaning, crew buses): 10% of 12 flights = 1.2 × several vehicles = ~10 vehicles.`,result:`~16 fuel/misc vehicles`},{heading:`Step 5: Total`,body:`Total slow-moving vehicles in peak hour = 9 + 6 + 75 + 16 = 106 ≈ 100 vehicles at any given time.`,result:`~100 ground vehicles`}],answer:`Approximately 100–120 slow-moving ground vehicles operate at a major Indian airport during peak hours.`,insight:`This is a structured estimation with multiple vehicle categories. The cargo vehicles are the largest contributor. A key assumption to flag to the interviewer: the 2-round-trips-per-hour productivity for cargo carts. More efficient airport operations could halve this number; less efficient operations could double it.`},
  {id:35,title:`LED Bulbs Sold Annually in a Highly Electrified South Indian State`,question:`Estimate the number of LED bulbs sold annually in a fully electrified south Indian state with a population of approximately 3.5 crore.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Market Sizing`,approach:`Calculate LED bulbs in use across residential and commercial segments separately, then apply the annual replacement rate (1/life) and new demand growth (5%).`,assumptions:[`State population: 3.5 crore. Average household size: 4 → 87.5 lakh households.`,`100% rural electrification; all households use electricity.`,`Average LED bulbs per household: Low income 4, Middle 8, High 15. Income split: Low 20%, Middle 60%, High 20%.`,`Average LED bulb life: 3 years (replacement rate = 1/3 of stock per year).`,`New demand from household growth: 5% annually.`,`Commercial establishment ratios: Retail 1/100 population, Services 1/200, F&B 1/500, Institutions 1/1,000, Offices 1/50.`,`The state has proactively promoted LED adoption through government energy efficiency programmes.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Residential LED bulbs in use`,body:`Low income (20% = 17.5L HH) × 4 bulbs = 70L.
Middle (60% = 52.5L HH) × 8 = 420L.
High (20% = 17.5L HH) × 15 = 262.5L.
Total residential bulbs = 752.5 lakh ≈ 750 lakh.`,result:`750 lakh residential bulbs`},{heading:`Step 2: Residential annual sales`,body:`Replacement = 750L ÷ 3 years = 250L.
New demand = 5% of 750L = 37.5L.
Residential annual sales = 287.5 lakh ≈ 290 lakh.`,result:`290 lakh residential/year`},{heading:`Step 3: Commercial establishments and bulbs`,body:`Population: 35L people.
Retail (35L÷100 = 3.5L establishments × 4 bulbs) = 14L.
Services (35L÷200 = 1.75L × 11) = 19.25L.
F&B (35L÷500 = 70K × 10) = 7L.
Institutions (35L÷1000 = 35K × 20) = 7L.
Offices (35L÷50 = 7L × 15) = 105L.
Total commercial bulbs = 152.25 lakh.`,result:`152 lakh commercial bulbs`},{heading:`Step 4: Commercial annual sales`,body:`Replacement = 152L ÷ 3 = 50.7L.
New demand = 5% × 152L = 7.6L.
Commercial sales = 58.3 lakh ≈ 58 lakh.`,result:`58 lakh commercial/year`},{heading:`Step 5: Total annual LED sales in this state`,body:`Total = 290L + 58L = 348 lakh ≈ 3.5 crore LED bulbs per year.`,result:`~3.5 crore LED bulbs/year`}],answer:`Approximately 3–4 crore LED bulbs are sold in the state annually.`,insight:`States with high electrification and proactive LED adoption programmes typically see near-total LED penetration in urban and peri-urban areas. Our estimate of ~3.5 crore LED bulbs/year is consistent with a state that has completed the LED transition and is now primarily in replacement mode rather than first-adoption mode.`},
  {id:36,title:`Total Ad Duration Streamed on a Video Platform Daily`,question:`Estimate the total duration (in seconds) of advertisements streamed on a major online video platform globally in one day.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Start with daily active users, apply the proportion who see ads, then model ad types and durations.`,assumptions:[`A major video platform (comparable to YouTube) has approximately 2 billion monthly active users.`,`50% use it daily → 1 billion daily active users.`,`50% of daily users encounter at least one ad during their session (the rest use premium/ad-free plans).`,`Ad-exposed users: 500 million. Short videos (<8 min): 60% of sessions = 300M; Long videos (>8 min): 40% = 200M.`,`Short videos: 1 ad per video. Long videos: 2 ads per video.`,`Ad types: Non-skippable (50%) avg 15 sec; Skippable but skipped (40%) avg 5 sec; Skippable but watched in full (10%) avg 20 sec.`,`Each user watches 1 video per session (conservative assumption).`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Short video ad duration`,body:`300M users × 1 ad/video.
Non-skippable (50% × 300M × 15s) = 2,250M seconds.
Skippable-skipped (40% × 300M × 5s) = 600M seconds.
Skippable-watched (10% × 300M × 20s) = 600M seconds.
Short video total = 3,450M seconds.`,result:`3,450M seconds (short videos)`},{heading:`Step 2: Long video ad duration`,body:`200M users × 2 ads/video.
Non-skippable (50% × 200M × 2 × 15s) = 3,000M seconds.
Skippable-skipped (40% × 200M × 2 × 5s) = 800M seconds.
Skippable-watched (10% × 200M × 2 × 20s) = 800M seconds.
Long video total = 4,600M seconds.`,result:`4,600M seconds (long videos)`},{heading:`Step 3: Total ad duration`,body:`Total = 3,450M + 4,600M = 8,050M seconds ≈ 8 billion seconds per day.`,result:`~8 billion seconds/day`}],answer:`Approximately 8 billion seconds (roughly 93,000 hours or ~3,900 days' worth) of advertisements are streamed globally on a major video platform per day.`,insight:`Key insight: The dominant driver is the volume of users — even a modest average of 16 seconds of ads per ad-exposed user translates into billions of seconds at 500 million users. The framework here is more important than the exact answer.`},
  {id:37,title:`Pairs of Shoes Sold in Mumbai Per Day`,question:`Estimate the number of pairs of covered shoes sold in Mumbai per day.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Estimate the total shoe stock in Mumbai by income/gender/age, divide by average useful life to get annual sales, then convert to daily.`,assumptions:[`Only covered shoes (formal, sports, casual) are counted; slippers, sandals, and flip-flops are excluded.`,`Mumbai population: 2 crore. Income split: Upper class 10% (2M), Middle class 30% (6M), Lower-middle 40% (8M), BPL 20% (4M).`,`Average pairs of shoes owned and life by segment and gender:`,`Upper class: Men 5 pairs (life 3 yrs), Women 5 pairs (3 yrs), Kids 4 pairs (life 2 yrs).`,`Middle class: Men 4 pairs (life 4 yrs), Women 4 pairs (4 yrs), Kids 3 pairs (3 yrs).`,`Lower-middle: Men 3 pairs (life 5 yrs), Women 2 pairs (5 yrs), Kids 2 pairs (5 yrs).`,`BPL: Men 1 pair (6 yrs), Women 0 pairs, Kids 0.5 pairs (6 yrs).`,`Gender/age split in each income segment: Men 35%, Women 35%, Kids 30%.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Annual shoe purchases — Upper class (2M)`,body:`Men (0.7M): 0.7M × 5 ÷ 3 = 1.17M pairs.
Women (0.7M): 0.7M × 5 ÷ 3 = 1.17M.
Kids (0.6M): 0.6M × 4 ÷ 2 = 1.20M.
Total: 3.54M pairs/yr.`,result:`3.54M upper class`},{heading:`Step 2: Middle class (6M)`,body:`Men (2.1M): 2.1M × 4 ÷ 4 = 2.10M.
Women (2.1M): 2.1M × 4 ÷ 4 = 2.10M.
Kids (1.8M): 1.8M × 3 ÷ 3 = 1.80M.
Total: 6.00M pairs/yr.`,result:`6.00M middle class`},{heading:`Step 3: Lower-middle (8M)`,body:`Men (2.8M): 2.8M × 3 ÷ 5 = 1.68M.
Women (2.8M): 2.8M × 2 ÷ 5 = 1.12M.
Kids (2.4M): 2.4M × 2 ÷ 5 = 0.96M.
Total: 3.76M pairs/yr.`,result:`3.76M lower-middle`},{heading:`Step 4: BPL (4M)`,body:`Men (1.2M): 1.2M × 1 ÷ 6 = 0.20M.
Women: 0. Kids (1.6M): 1.6M × 0.5 ÷ 6 = 0.13M.
Total: 0.33M pairs/yr.`,result:`0.33M BPL`},{heading:`Step 5: Daily sales`,body:`Total annual = 3.54 + 6.00 + 3.76 + 0.33 = 13.63M.
Daily = 13.63M ÷ 365 = 37,343 ≈ 37,000 pairs per day.`,result:`~37,000 pairs/day`}],answer:`Approximately 35,000–40,000 pairs of covered shoes are sold in Mumbai per day.`,insight:`Sanity check from supply side: If Mumbai has ~600 sq km of commercial area with roughly 7 footwear shops per sq km = 4,200 shops. Each shop sells ~9 pairs per day → 37,800 pairs — consistent with our demand-side estimate.`},
  {id:38,title:`Home Renovation Market Size in a Major large Indian Metro`,question:`Estimate the size of the residential home renovation market in a large large Indian city with a population of approximately 1 crore.`,difficulty:`Easy`,category:`Market Sizing`,approach:`Identify households in the target income segments (Middle, Upper-middle, Upper class), apply renovation cycle frequency and average renovation spend per house.`,assumptions:[`City population: 1 crore. Average household size: 4 → 25 lakh households.`,`BPL (20%) and low-middle class (35%) excluded — they do not undertake formal renovation.`,`Target segments: Middle class (30% = 7.5L HH), Upper-middle (10% = 2.5L HH), Upper class (5% = 1.25L HH).`,`Renovation cycle: Middle class every 15 years; Upper-middle every 12 years; Upper class every 10 years.`,`Average house price: Middle Rs 25L, Upper-middle Rs 75L, Upper class Rs 1.5 crore.`,`Renovation spend as % of house value: Middle 6%, Upper-middle 8%, Upper class 10%.`,`The city has a rapidly growing IT and services economy driving demand for premium residential upgrades.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Houses renovated per year`,body:`Middle class: 7.5L HH ÷ 15 yrs = 50,000 houses/year.
Upper-middle: 2.5L ÷ 12 = 20,833 ≈ 21,000 houses/year.
Upper class: 1.25L ÷ 10 = 12,500 houses/year.`,result:`Middle 50K · Upper-mid 21K · Upper 12.5K`},{heading:`Step 2: Renovation spend per house`,body:`Middle: Rs 25L × 6% = Rs 1.5 lakh.
Upper-middle: Rs 75L × 8% = Rs 6 lakh.
Upper class: Rs 1.5 crore × 10% = Rs 15 lakh.`,result:`Middle Rs 1.5L · Upper-mid Rs 6L · Upper Rs 15L`},{heading:`Step 3: Total market size`,body:`Middle: 50,000 × Rs 1.5L = Rs 750 crore.
Upper-middle: 21,000 × Rs 6L = Rs 1,260 crore.
Upper class: 12,500 × Rs 15L = Rs 1,875 crore.
Total = Rs 750 + Rs 1,260 + Rs 1,875 = Rs 3,885 crore ≈ Rs 3,900 crore.`,result:`Rs ~3,900 crore`}],answer:`The home renovation market in the city is approximately Rs 3,500–4,000 crore annually.`,insight:`In large metro cities with a strong professional class, the upper segment contributes ~50% of total renovation market value despite being the smallest segment — a classic 80/20 pattern in discretionary spending.`},
  {id:39,title:`Annual Revenue of a 4-Screen Multiplex`,question:`Estimate the annual revenue of a multiplex cinema with 4 screens.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Revenue Estimation`,approach:`Calculate revenue per screen per day across weekdays and weekends, then scale to the annual calendar.`,assumptions:[`Each screen: 300 seats, 4 shows per day (weekday) / 5 shows (weekend).`,`Ticket price: Rs 250 per seat (uniform, all shows).`,`Weekday occupancy: 60%. Weekend occupancy: 90%.`,`50% of footfall parks a vehicle (parking charge Rs 50 each).`,`50% of footfall buys food and beverages (average spend Rs 150).`,`Year: 260 weekdays and 105 weekend days.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Footfall per screen per day`,body:`Weekday footfall: 300 seats × 60% occupancy × 4 shows = 720 people.
Weekend footfall: 300 × 90% × 5 shows = 1,350 people.`,result:`Weekday 720 · Weekend 1,350 per screen`},{heading:`Step 2: Revenue per screen per day`,body:`Weekday:
  Ticket: 720 × Rs 250 = Rs 1,80,000.
  Parking: 720 × 50% × Rs 50 = Rs 18,000.
  F&B: 720 × 50% × Rs 150 = Rs 54,000.
  Total: Rs 2,52,000 per screen.
Weekend:
  Ticket: 1,350 × Rs 250 = Rs 3,37,500.
  Parking: 1,350 × 50% × Rs 50 = Rs 33,750.
  F&B: 1,350 × 50% × Rs 150 = Rs 1,01,250.
  Total: Rs 4,72,500 per screen.`,result:`Weekday Rs 2.52L · Weekend Rs 4.73L per screen`},{heading:`Step 3: Revenue for 4 screens`,body:`Weekday: Rs 2,52,000 × 4 screens = Rs 10,08,000.
Weekend: Rs 4,72,500 × 4 screens = Rs 18,90,000.`,result:`Daily: Weekday Rs 10.1L · Weekend Rs 18.9L`},{heading:`Step 4: Annual revenue`,body:`Weekday annual: Rs 10,08,000 × 260 = Rs 26.2 crore.
Weekend annual: Rs 18,90,000 × 105 = Rs 19.8 crore.
Total annual revenue = Rs 46 crore ≈ Rs 42–46 crore.`,result:`Rs ~42–46 crore/year`}],answer:`A 4-screen multiplex earns approximately Rs 42–46 crore in annual revenue.`,insight:`Listed multiplex chains (PVR, Inox) report average annual revenue of Rs 3–5 crore per screen across their portfolios. For 4 screens, that implies Rs 12–20 crore — lower than our estimate. The gap reflects that our model assumes higher occupancy and a more premium ticket price than the company-wide blended average. A well-located, premium urban multiplex could indeed approach Rs 40+ crore annually.`},
  {id:40,title:`Monthly Revenue of a DTH Provider from Delhi`,question:`Estimate the monthly revenue of a leading DTH (Direct-to-Home TV) service provider from its Delhi subscriber base.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Revenue Estimation`,approach:`Estimate the number of DTH subscribers in Delhi from the eligible household base, apply market share, and multiply by average monthly subscription value.`,assumptions:[`Delhi population: 2 crore. Households: 50 lakh (average size 4).`,`TV penetration by income: High income (20% = 10L HH) 100%; Middle income (30% = 15L HH) 90%; Low income (30% = 15L HH) 50%; BPL (20% = 10L HH) 0%.`,`TV-owning households: 10L + 13.5L + 7.5L = 31L. BPL excluded.`,`DTH market share of target provider: High income 40%, Middle income 30%, Low income 20%.`,`DTH subscribers: High (10L × 40%) = 4L; Middle (13.5L × 30%) = 4.05L; Low (7.5L × 20%) = 1.5L. Total = 9.55L.`,`Monthly ARPU (Average Revenue Per User): High income Rs 750; Middle Rs 500; Low Rs 250.`,`Multi-connection households (High income: 1.5 connections per subscriber; Middle: 1.25; Low: 1.0).`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: DTH subscriber count`,body:`High income: 4.0 lakh subscribers × 1.5 connections = 6.0 lakh connections.
Middle income: 4.05L × 1.25 = 5.06L connections.
Low income: 1.5L × 1.0 = 1.5L connections.
Total connections = 12.56 lakh.`,result:`12.56 lakh connections`},{heading:`Step 2: Monthly revenue by segment`,body:`High: 6.0L connections × Rs 750 = Rs 45 crore.
Middle: 5.06L × Rs 500 = Rs 25.3 crore.
Low: 1.5L × Rs 250 = Rs 3.75 crore.`,result:`High Rs 45Cr · Middle Rs 25.3Cr · Low Rs 3.75Cr`},{heading:`Step 3: Total monthly revenue`,body:`Total = Rs 45 + Rs 25.3 + Rs 3.75 = Rs 74.05 crore ≈ Rs 74 crore.`,result:`Rs ~74 crore/month`}],answer:`A leading DTH provider earns approximately Rs 70–75 crore per month from Delhi.`,insight:`Listed DTH players reported total Indian revenues of Rs 8,000–10,000 crore per year in 2022-23. Delhi accounts for roughly 8–10% of India's TV households, implying Delhi revenue of Rs 640–1,000 crore per year = Rs 55–85 crore per month — consistent with our estimate.`},
  {id:41,title:`Annual Toll Tax Collected Across India`,question:`Estimate the total toll tax collected across all national highway toll plazas in India per year.`,difficulty:`Hard`,category:`Revenue Estimation`,approach:`Estimate the number of toll plazas in India, model vehicle traffic and toll rates per plaza per day, and scale annually.`,assumptions:[`India's national highway network: approximately 1,46,000 km (NHAI data).`,`Toll plazas are typically spaced every 60 km on national highways → number of plazas = 1,46,000 ÷ 60 ≈ 2,433, rounded to 2,400.`,`Each plaza has 4 active lanes on average.`,`Vehicle processing speed: 30 sec/vehicle at peak; 60 sec mid; 90 sec off-peak.`,`Hours per day by load: Peak (10am–6pm, 8 hrs), Mid (6pm–2am, 8 hrs), Off-peak (2am–10am, 8 hrs).`,`Vehicles processed per lane: Peak 8hrs÷30s = 960; Mid 8hrs÷60s = 480; Off-peak 8hrs÷90s = 320.`,`Vehicle type mix: Small 50% (Rs 100 toll), Medium 30% (Rs 200), Large 20% (Rs 400). Weighted average toll = Rs 170 at peak, Rs 210 at mid, Rs 310 at off-peak.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Vehicles processed per lane per day`,body:`Peak: 960 vehicles → revenue = 960 × Rs 170 = Rs 1,63,200.
Mid: 480 × Rs 210 = Rs 1,00,800.
Off-peak: 320 × Rs 310 = Rs 99,200.
Revenue per lane per day = Rs 3,63,200 ≈ Rs 3.6 lakh.`,result:`Rs 3.6 lakh/lane/day`},{heading:`Step 2: Revenue per plaza per day`,body:`4 lanes × Rs 3.6 lakh = Rs 14.4 lakh per plaza per day.`,result:`Rs 14.4 lakh/plaza/day`},{heading:`Step 3: Annual revenue from all plazas`,body:`2,400 plazas × Rs 14.4 lakh/day × 365 days = 2,400 × Rs 5,256 lakh = Rs 1,26,14,400 lakh ≈ Rs 1,26,144 crore ≈ Rs 1.26 lakh crore.`,result:`Rs ~1.26 lakh crore`},{heading:`Step 4: Adjusted estimate`,body:`Accounting for ~30% non-toll stretches (urban bypasses, partially constructed sections) where no toll is collected:
Adjusted = Rs 1.26 lakh crore × 70% = Rs 88,000 crore ≈ Rs 85,000–90,000 crore.`,result:`Rs ~85,000–90,000 crore/year`}],answer:`India's national highway toll collection is approximately Rs 85,000–90,000 crore per year.`,insight:`NHAI actually reports annual toll collection of approximately Rs 40,000–50,000 crore in recent years (FY23: Rs 41,000 crore). Our estimate is approximately 2× too high — primarily because the vehicle processing model overstates the proportion of high-toll heavy vehicles and the utilisation of plaza capacity. A more realistic vehicle mix (70% small at Rs 70 rather than Rs 100) would bring the estimate to Rs 50,000–55,000 crore.`},
  {id:42,title:`Instant Coffee Revenue in Mumbai on a Weekday`,question:`Estimate the revenue generated from consumption of instant coffee (sachets, jars, and pods) in Mumbai on a typical weekday.`,difficulty:`Hard`,category:`Revenue Estimation`,approach:`Segment Mumbai's population by income and estimate at-home versus out-of-home coffee drinking, applying segment-specific prices per cup.`,assumptions:[`Mumbai population: 2 crore. Income split: Low 20% (40L), Middle 40% (80L), High 20% (40L). (Remaining 20% are BPL — not relevant.)`,`Coffee-drinking age: 15–60 years = 60% of population.`,`Coffee penetration among age-eligible consumers: Low income 5% (mostly stall-bought), Middle 40%, High 60%.`,`Average cups per day per coffee drinker: 2 cups.`,`Coffee type and price per cup: Low income — chicory-blend at Rs 2/cup (stalls). Middle — instant sachet at home at Rs 4/cup, stall at Rs 5/cup (split 50:50). High — freeze-dried home brew at Rs 20/cup, café at Rs 50/cup (split 40:60).`,`Market share of a leading instant coffee brand: 50% of all at-home instant coffee.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Low income coffee drinkers`,body:`40L people × 60% age-eligible = 24L. × 5% penetration = 1.2L coffee drinkers.
1.2L × 2 cups × Rs 2 = Rs 4.8L total revenue. Brand share (stall supply) = 50% → Rs 2.4L.`,result:`Rs 2.4 lakh (low income)`},{heading:`Step 2: Middle income coffee drinkers`,body:`80L × 60% = 48L. × 40% = 19.2L drinkers.
At home (50%): 9.6L × 2 cups × Rs 4 = Rs 76.8L; brand share 50% → Rs 38.4L.
Stall (50%): 9.6L × 2 × Rs 5 = Rs 96L; stall wholesale brand share 50% → Rs 48L.
Middle income brand revenue = Rs 38.4L + Rs 48L = Rs 86.4L.`,result:`Rs 86.4 lakh (middle income)`},{heading:`Step 3: High income coffee drinkers`,body:`40L × 60% = 24L. × 60% = 14.4L drinkers.
At home (40%): 5.76L × 2 × Rs 20 = Rs 230.4L; brand share 50% → Rs 115.2L.
Café (60%): 8.64L × 2 × Rs 50 = Rs 864L; brand at cafés ~10% share → Rs 86.4L.
High income brand revenue = Rs 115.2L + Rs 86.4L = Rs 201.6L.`,result:`Rs 201.6 lakh (high income)`},{heading:`Step 4: Total revenue`,body:`Total = Rs 2.4L + Rs 86.4L + Rs 201.6L = Rs 290.4L ≈ Rs 290 lakh = Rs 2.9 crore.`,result:`Rs ~2.9 crore/weekday`}],answer:`Revenue from a leading instant coffee brand's consumption in Mumbai on a weekday is approximately Rs 2.5–3 crore.`,insight:`Nestlé India's total coffee revenues (Nescafé, Sunrise) are approximately Rs 2,500–3,000 crore annually across India. Mumbai's share (~10%) would be Rs 250–300 crore/year = Rs 70–80 lakh/day. Our estimate of Rs 2.9 crore/day is about 4× higher, primarily because we are estimating total revenue from all points of consumption (including cafés), not just packaged retail sales.`},
  {id:43,title:`Snapchat Streaks Shared Per Day in India`,question:`Estimate the number of Snapchat streaks shared in India per day.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Filter India's urban population to active Snapchat streak users and multiply by daily streaks sent.`,assumptions:[`Urban population of India: ~52 crore (India pop 130 crore × 40%). (Rural Snapchat usage is negligible.)`,`Age filter: 0–12 years (no smartphone): ~90M excluded. 60+ years (minimal usage): ~75M excluded. Active age (12–60): ~35.5 crore.`,`Income split of 12–60 urban cohort: Lower class 20% = 7.1cr, Middle class 60% = 21.3cr, Upper class 20% = 7.1cr.`,`Smartphone penetration: Lower 60%, Middle 80%, Upper 95%.`,`Social media usage among smartphone users: Lower 50%, Middle 75%, Upper 75%.`,`Snapchat usage among social media users: 30% (all classes — Snapchat is popular across middle-class Indian youth).`,`Of Snapchat users, percentage actively maintaining streaks: 33%.`,`Average streaks sent per day per active user: 8.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Snapchat users in India`,body:`Lower: 7.1cr × 60% × 50% × 30% = 0.64cr.
Middle: 21.3cr × 80% × 75% × 30% = 3.83cr.
Upper: 7.1cr × 95% × 75% × 30% = 1.52cr.
Total Snapchat users = 6.0 crore.
Adjust for rural India (+10%): 6.0 × 1.1 = 6.6 crore ≈ 6.5 crore.`,result:`~6.5 crore Snapchat users`},{heading:`Step 2: Active streak users`,body:`6.5 crore × 33% maintaining streaks = 2.15 crore streak users.`,result:`2.15 crore streak users`},{heading:`Step 3: Daily streaks sent`,body:`2.15 crore × 8 streaks/day = 17.2 crore streaks ≈ 17 crore streaks per day.`,result:`~17 crore streaks/day`}],answer:`Approximately 15–20 crore Snapchat streaks are sent in India per day.`,insight:`Snap Inc. does not publish India-specific streak data. As a reference, Snap had approximately 750 million monthly active users globally as of 2024, with India being one of the largest markets. Our estimate implies ~8.5% of global monthly actives are daily streak senders in India, which is plausible given India's young urban internet population.`},
  {id:44,title:`Litres of Paint Used to Paint Private Cars in India Annually`,question:`Estimate the total litres of paint used annually to paint private cars in India.`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Estimate new car paint (factory) and used car paint (repair/resale) separately by income segment.`,assumptions:[`India has ~350 million households (140 crore ÷ 4 average size).`,`Car ownership by income: Low & Lower-middle (75% = 262.5M HH) → 2% own cars. Upper-middle (20% = 70M HH) → 20% own cars. High income (5% = 17.5M HH) → 50% own cars.`,`Average car life: Low owners 7 years, Upper-middle 6 years, High income 5 years.`,`Annual replacement (cars leaving fleet): Low 5M÷7 = 0.7M; Upper-mid 14M÷6 = 2.3M; High 8.75M÷5 = 1.75M.`,`New vs used paint demand: Higher income households buy mostly new; lower income buy mostly used.`,`Litres of paint per car: New paint (full factory coat) 5 litres; Used/repair paint 1 litre (spot and touch-up).`,`High income: 50% new, 50% used. Upper-mid: 15% new, 85% used. Low: 0% new, 100% used.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Total cars per segment`,body:`Low (262.5M × 2%) = 5.25M cars.
Upper-mid (70M × 20%) = 14M cars.
High (17.5M × 50%) = 8.75M cars.`,result:`Low 5.25M · Upper-mid 14M · High 8.75M`},{heading:`Step 2: Annual turnover and paint demand`,body:`Low (0.75M annual, 100% used): 0.75M × 0% × 5 + 0.75M × 100% × 1 = 0.75M litres.
Upper-mid (2.3M annual, 15% new): 2.3M × 15% × 5 + 2.3M × 85% × 1 = 1.73M + 1.96M = 3.69M litres.
High (1.75M annual, 50% new): 1.75M × 50% × 5 + 1.75M × 50% × 1.5 = 4.38M + 1.31M = 5.69M litres.`,result:`Low 0.75M · Upper-mid 3.69M · High 5.69M`},{heading:`Step 3: Total paint`,body:`Total = 0.75M + 3.69M + 5.69M = 10.13M litres ≈ 10 million litres.`,result:`~10 million litres/year`}],answer:`Approximately 10 million litres (1 crore litres) of paint are used annually in India to paint private cars.`,insight:`Automotive paint is a specialised segment. India's automotive paint market is valued at approximately Rs 5,000–6,000 crore, with OEM (factory) segment being the largest. At Rs 500/litre average for automotive paint, 10M litres = Rs 500 crore — which is plausible as the aftermarket/repair segment alone.`},
  {id:45,title:`Bullets Fired in India Annually`,question:`Estimate the total number of bullets fired in India in a year, including by defence, police, licensed gun owners, and security personnel.`,difficulty:`Hard`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Segment bullet users into non-civilians (armed forces and police) and civilians (licensed gun holders and security personnel), then estimate annual rounds fired per person.`,assumptions:[`India's population: 140 crore. Armed forces: ~1.4 million (1 per 1,000). Police force: ~1.4 million.`,`Licensed civilian gun holders: approximately 28 lakh (0.2% of population), including sportspersons and security guards.`,`Training bullets (training vs live fire): Training intensity is higher for new recruits.`,`Armed forces — training: New recruits (10% of force = 1.4L) → 300 shots × 250 days = 75,000 shots/yr; Existing (90% = 12.6L) → 120 shots × 100 days = 12,000 shots/yr.`,`Police force — training: New recruits (10% = 1.4L) → 120 shots × 250 = 30,000; Existing → 60 shots × 50 = 3,000.`,`Live fire (additional): Armed forces existing: 400 shots/yr. Police existing: 200 shots/yr.`,`Security personnel (2.8L, 0.2%): 50 shots × 50 days = 2,500/yr. Sportspersons (28K): 4 matches × 100 shots = 400/yr.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Armed forces bullets`,body:`New recruits (1.4L): 1.4L × 75,000 = 10,500M shots.
Existing (12.6L): 12.6L × (12,000 training + 400 live) = 12.6L × 12,400 = 15,624M shots.
Armed forces total = 26,124M ≈ 26 billion.`,result:`~26 billion (armed forces)`},{heading:`Step 2: Police force bullets`,body:`New (1.4L): 1.4L × 30,000 = 4,200M.
Existing (12.6L): 12.6L × (3,000 + 200 live) = 12.6L × 3,200 = 4,032M.
Police total = 8,232M ≈ 8 billion.`,result:`~8 billion (police)`},{heading:`Step 3: Civilian bullets`,body:`Security guards (2.8L): 2.8L × 2,500 = 700M.
Sportspersons (28K): 28K × 400 = 11.2M ≈ negligible.
Unlicensed: assumed negligible in formal accounting.
Civilian total ≈ 710M ≈ 0.7 billion.`,result:`~0.7 billion (civilians)`},{heading:`Step 4: Total bullets fired`,body:`Total = 26B + 8B + 0.7B = 34.7 billion ≈ 35 billion bullets per year.`,result:`~35 billion bullets/year`}],answer:`Approximately 35 billion bullets are fired in India annually, with armed forces and police accounting for over 99% of this volume.`,insight:`This is primarily a framework exercise. The 80/20 rule applies strongly: focus on non-civilian users, as civilian consumption is negligible by comparison. The key judgement calls are the training intensity for new recruits versus existing personnel.`},
  {id:46,title:`Chess Moves Played in India Per Day`,question:`Estimate the total number of chess moves played in India in one day (online and offline combined).`,difficulty:`Moderate`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Estimate the active chess player base in India, segment by skill level, apply daily activity rates and game formats to calculate total moves.`,assumptions:[`Total registered chess players in India: approximately 1 million (based on national federation estimates).`,`Player composition: Professional 0.5% = 5,000; Intermediate 15% = 1,50,000; Amateur 84.5% = 8,45,000.`,`Daily active players: Professional 50%, Intermediate 25%, Amateur 10%.`,`Three game formats — Bullet (<1 min): 40 moves avg; Blitz (1–5 min): 50 moves avg; Classical (>5 min): 60 moves avg.`,`Daily games per active player: Bullet 10, Blitz 2, Classical 0.1 (all skill levels; professionals may play more sessions).`,`India has seen a dramatic rise in chess participation post-2023, driven by online platforms and high-profile national players.`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Active players per tier`,body:`Professional: 5,000 × 50% = 2,500.
Intermediate: 1,50,000 × 25% = 37,500.
Amateur: 8,45,000 × 10% = 84,500.`,result:`2,500 + 37,500 + 84,500 = 124,500 active`},{heading:`Step 2: Moves from Bullet games`,body:`Each tier: 10 games/day × 40 moves.
Total bullet moves = (2,500 + 37,500 + 84,500) × 10 × 40 = 1,24,500 × 400 = 49.8M.`,result:`~50M moves (bullet)`},{heading:`Step 3: Moves from Blitz games`,body:`Each tier: 2 games/day × 50 moves.
Total blitz moves = 1,24,500 × 2 × 50 = 12.45M.`,result:`~12.45M moves (blitz)`},{heading:`Step 4: Moves from Classical games`,body:`Each tier: 0.1 games/day × 60 moves.
Classical moves = 1,24,500 × 0.1 × 60 = 747,000 ≈ 0.75M.`,result:`~0.75M moves (classical)`},{heading:`Step 5: Total`,body:`Total = 49.8M + 12.45M + 0.75M = 63M ≈ 6.3 crore chess moves per day.`,result:`~6.3 crore moves/day`}],answer:`Approximately 6–7 crore chess moves are played in India per day.`,insight:`India has produced more chess grandmasters than any country outside Russia. The online chess boom (Chess.com, Lichess) has dramatically expanded the active player base beyond registered OTB players. Our estimate counts registered players only — actual daily moves including casual online games could easily be 5–10× higher.`},
  {id:47,title:`Injections Administered Daily in a Major Indian City`,question:`Estimate the number of injections administered in a major Indian city with a population of approximately 80 lakh in one day.`,difficulty:`Hard`,category:`Volume Estimation`,approach:`Segment the population by age group (children, adults, seniors), estimate doctor visit frequency and injection rates by income group, and separately calculate self-administered insulin injections.`,assumptions:[`City population: 80 lakh. Age segments: Children 1–14 yrs (25% = 20L), Adults 15–60 yrs (65% = 52L), Senior citizens 60+ (10% = 8L).`,`Income segments within each age group: Lower income 30%, Middle/Upper-middle 60%, High income 10%.`,`Doctor visits per year: Children (Lower 1, Middle 2, High 4); Adults (Lower 1, Middle 4, High 6); Seniors (Lower 2, Middle 4, High 6).`,`Proportion of visits requiring blood tests: ~10% across all groups.`,`Proportion where injection is administered: Children Lower 30%, High 40%; Adults Lower 5%, Middle 10%, High 15%; Seniors Lower 20%, Middle 30%, High 40%.`,`Diabetic population: 5% of total = 4 lakh. Each requires 1 insulin self-injection per day.`,`India has a high and rising diabetes burden — approximately 101 million diabetics nationally as of 2023 (IDF Atlas data).`],steps:[{heading:`Step 1: Child injections (professionally administered)`,body:`Lower income (30% = 6L): 6L × 1 visit/yr × 30% injection rate = 1.8L injections/yr.
Middle income (60% = 12L): 12L × 2 × 35% = 8.4L/yr.
High income (10% = 2L): 2L × 4 × 40% = 3.2L/yr.
Total children = 13.4L/yr ÷ 365 = 3,671/day.`,result:`~3,700 child injections/day`},{heading:`Step 2: Adult injections`,body:`Lower (30% = 15.6L): 15.6L × 1 × 5% = 0.78L/yr.
Middle (60% = 31.2L): 31.2L × 4 × 10% = 12.48L/yr.
High (10% = 5.2L): 5.2L × 6 × 15% = 4.68L/yr.
Total adults = 17.94L/yr ÷ 365 = 4,915/day.`,result:`~4,900 adult injections/day`},{heading:`Step 3: Senior citizen injections`,body:`Lower (30% = 2.4L): 2.4L × 2 × 20% = 0.96L/yr.
Middle (60% = 4.8L): 4.8L × 4 × 30% = 5.76L/yr.
High (10% = 0.8L): 0.8L × 6 × 40% = 1.92L/yr.
Total seniors = 8.64L/yr ÷ 365 = 2,367/day.`,result:`~2,400 senior injections/day`},{heading:`Step 4: Insulin injections (self-administered)`,body:`Diabetic population = 5% × 80L = 4L people.
4 lakh diabetics × 1 insulin injection/day = 4,00,000 injections/day.`,result:`4,00,000 insulin/day`},{heading:`Step 5: Total daily injections`,body:`Professional: 3,700 + 4,900 + 2,400 = 11,000.
Self-administered: 4,00,000.
Total = 4,11,000 ≈ 4 lakh injections per day.`,result:`~4 lakh injections/day`}],answer:`Approximately 4 lakh injections are administered in the city daily, with insulin self-injections by diabetics being by far the largest single contributor.`,insight:`The insulin self-injection segment dominates the total count, contributing 97%+ of all daily injections. Clinically administered injections (blood tests, therapeutic) are significant but small by comparison. Always clarify with the interviewer whether to include self-administered injections — it changes the answer by an order of magnitude.`}
];